<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An Expanded Arab Summit Likely: Egyptian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The holding of an expanded Arab
summit is likely under the current circumstances, Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that President Hosni Mubarak has
expressed Egypt's interest in and desire for holding an Arab
summit on that scale.
</P>
<P>
But high-level contacts need to be conducted at the right time
"to ensure the concurrence of Arab parties and thus provide the
propitious climate," Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Arabs are currently at the stage of coordination
and consultation among the five sides, namely Egypt, Jordan,
Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians, directly involved in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has called for a meeting among leaders of Egypt,
Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians to forge a unified
stance on the peace process in light of the victory of Ehud Barak,
moderate leader of the Israeli opposition Labor party, in the May
17 elections.
</P>
<P>
Discussions are under way among the five parties for the
possible convocation of the summit, which might lead to an
expanded Arab summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Coordination between Egypt and Syria constitutes an integral
part of the discussions among the Arab countries concerned, Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister flew to Damascus on Saturday and
held talks with his Syrian counterpart Farouq al-Sharaa and
President Hafez al-Assad in a bid to persuade Syria to take part
in the proposed summit.
</P>
<P>
Syria has showed little interest in the meeting as it is still
keeping distance from the Palestinians due to the Palestinians'
signing of interim peace accords separately with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moussa reiterated that Egypt is ready to give a momentum to the
peace efforts and only accepts a balanced peace based on the
land-for-peace principle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
