<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Needs 2 Billion Dollars Investment in Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Iran needs 2 billion U.S. dollars
investment to boost its energy to meet the country's growing
electricity consumption, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
on Sunday quoted Energy Minister Habibollah Bitaraf as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bitaraf told IRNA Saturday in Vienna at the end of his
three-day official visit to Austria that Iran's electricity
consumption growth rate stands at 7 percent or 2,000 megawatts
annually.
</P>
<P>
He said that investment in the transfer and distribution
sectors would be made totally in rials while in production
sector, 40 percent of the investment would be made in foreign
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Iranian Energy Ministry needs 600 million
dollars investment in foreign exchanges and 1.4 billion dollars
in rials every year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's electricity output has reached 102 billion
kilowatts-hour in the past Iranian year which ended on March 20,
Iranian Deputy Energy Minister for Electricity Affairs Mohammad
Mallaki said last month.
</P>
<P>
Mallaki said the country's electricity output would increase
to 108 billion kilowatts-hour in the current Iranian year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
