<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King in Egypt for Summit Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
began talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Sunday evening
on the latest developments in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah arrived in Cairo earlier in the day for a two-day
visit and went straight into the talks, also attended by senior
officials of both countries and top aides of the two
leaders, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks are expected to cover Mubarak's call for a summit
among Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians, the news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will review the coordination and consultations
among the Arab parties on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Following the victory of Ehud Barak, moderate leader of
Israel's opposition Labor party, in the May 17 elections, Mubarak
called for the five-way summit in a bid to forge a unified Arab
stance on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Barak has pledged to push the peace talks with the Palestinians
forward and resume negotiations with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first stop of the Jordanian king's ongoing tour,
which will also take him to Algeria, Tunisia and France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
