<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Warns Against Israeli Settlement Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Sunday warned against Israel's provocative
measures on settlement expansion in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing Israeli Likud government led by Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has decided to add 10 square kilometers to the
settlement of Maale Adumim, east of Jerusalem, where 25,000 Jewish
settlers are living.
</P>
<P>
With the expansion, Maale Adumim will border on Jerusalem and
further cut off the eastern sector of the city, which the
Palestinians want as a future capital, from its West Bank
hinterland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Hungary's new
ambassador to Egypt, Abdel-Meguid said the Israeli move "will only
complicate the situation and do not serve confidence-building
trends" between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The step will only place more obstacles to the Mideast peace
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
An enlarged Maale Adumim will also make it more difficult for
Israel and the Palestinians to reach a creative solution to the
future of Jerusalem, the most sticky issue in their peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Little progress has been made in the Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations since 1996 when Netanyahu came to power due to, among
other things, Israel's intransigent policy on settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
Hope seems to have been brought back to the peace process after
Ehud Barak, moderate leader of the Israel opposition Labor party,
was elected the country's next prime minister. The Palestinians
have called on him to speak out against the outgoing government's
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
