<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African States Agree to Formulate Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda,
members of the East African Cooperation (EAC), have agreed to
review the banking acts in their countries in a move to formulate
common regional banking laws.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has been reached by Tanzanian Finance Minister
Daniel Yona and his Kenyan and Ugandan counterparts Francis
Masakhalia and Gerald Ssendaula during their third pre-budget
consultative meeting in Arusha, north Tanzania, media reports said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was held last Friday, recommended that a
team of six officials comprising directors of supervision and
legal counsels from each of the central banks of the three
countries undertake this task.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers stressed the need to maintain the
macro-economic stability in the region and promote EAC as a single
market and investment area.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also proposed that the three countries should
implement zero tariff trade and harmonize common external tariff
by July 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it has been agreed that a conference against money
laundering for eastern African will be held in the Tanzanian
capital Dar es Salaam next August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
