<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shas Party Leader Tries to Overturn Graft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Aryeh Deri, leader of Israel's
powerful religious Shas party, submitted his appeal to the
Supreme Court on Sunday in a bid to overturn his conviction by the
Jerusalem District Court on charges of graft.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said that Deri presented a 75-page appeal to
Supreme Court President Aharon Barak on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The appeal reportedly challenged nearly every decision and
sentence against Deri by the district court.
</P>
<P>
Deri claimed that the court drew most of its conclusions based
on circumstantialities, rather than evidence.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court is going to determine whether the appeal will
be heard by a regular panel of three judges or by a wider
panel. And it will also set a date for the hearing of the case in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
Deri was convicted of bribe-taking, fraud and breach of public
trust by the Jerusalem District Court last month, and was
sentenced to four years in prison later.
</P>
<P>
At Deri's request, the court delayed the implementation of the
sentence until Deri had exhausted his right to appeal the decision
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The Shas party won 17 seats in the 120-member Knesset
(parliament) in the May 17 elections, an amazing growth from 10
seats in the last Knesset.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak was hesitant at bringing
Shas into his new coalition government as many left-wing political
figures refused to accept Shas with convicted Deri as its head.
</P>
<P>
If Deri could be acquitted by the Supreme Court, it would be
easier for Shas to join the new government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
