<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Sets up Voluntary AIDS Testing Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Voluntary Counselling and
Testing Centers for AIDS tests are being established in most urban
centers to offer AIDS tests at a subsidized fee.
</P>
<P>
National AIDS Council Program Director Everisto Marowa told the
Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana Sunday that the testing centers would
also provide information to the community.
</P>
<P>
He said Bulawayo, the country's second largest city, was the
first to have a test center two years back, but the rest are in
Harare, the capital. There will be more centers opening up in
other regions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The cost of these tests was being subsidized by a number of
donors as a contribution to the control of the spread of the
deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
He hoped this new development would persuade more people to
seek tests for the virus.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that testing was not the solution to
everything, but counselling and the injection of vital information
on HIV/Aids would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
AIDS continued to have a devastating impact on Zimbabwe's
population of 12.5 million, with about 25 percent of the adults
population infected.
</P>
<P>
Projections for the year 2005 estimated that 1.2 million
Zimbabweans would have died from the disease and more nearly one
million children would lose one or both parents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
