<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-30 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Urged to Halt Settlements Immediately </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Sunday sent a strong-worded message to Israeli
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, urging him to break his silence
and stop the intensified Jewish settlement activities in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Barak is called upon to lift his silence and take steps to
stop measures taken by Netanyahu which will destroy the peace
process," said Tayeb Abdul Rahim, Secretary of PNA Chairman
Yasser Arafat, referring to outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the National Conference to Confront Settlements held
in Ramallah, Abdul Rahim also called for physical confrontation
against Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"We are called upon to translate our anger into confrontation
to stop the settlement construction," he told hundreds of
representatives of various Palestinian political factions.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held after the Israeli government decided last
week to expand Maale Adumin, the biggest Jewish settlement in the
West Bank, to link it to the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The expansion decision was among a series of settlement
activities taking place before and after the Israeli general
elections on May 17, including grabbing of hilltops in the
West Bank and the construction of Jewish houses in Har Homa
and the Ras El-Amoud neighborhood, both in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
These stepped-up activities were widely seen as attempts by
Jewish settlers as well as the outgoing government to create
facts on the ground before the new government begins final
status talks with the Palestinians, in which the fate of
settlements will be discussed.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Maale Adumin, its extension to the borders of
Jerusalem would form a band of Israeli-held land that cuts the
West Bank in half, thus destroying the continuity of
Palestinian-controlled areas, which the Palestinians desperately
need when they establish an independent state in the future.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who has pledged to revive the peace talks with the
Palestinians, has stated that he would keep large blocs of
settlements under Israeli control, implying that small and
isolated ones will be dismantled.
</P>
<P>
But he has kept silent on the increasing settlement activities
since he defeated Netanyahu in the prime ministerial race. His
aides said it's inappropriate for him to speak out since he is
still conducting coalition talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are concerned that he might have his hands
tied if he finally forms a coalition including right-wing parties
such as the Likud and the National Religious Party, which
favor expanding Jewish settlements activities.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Qureia, speaker of the Palestinian Legislative Council,
warned that the Palestinians would not go into any new
negotiations if the new government under Barak does not take firm
measures to stop the settlements.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, the top Palestine Liberation Organization
official in East Jerusalem, called the situation "very critical."
</P>
<P>
"If there are no confrontations on grounds all over the
area, neither Barak's promises, nor certain principles can end
settlements," he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference called on Palestinians in the West Bank and
Gaza to stage large-scale protest against Jewish settlements on
Thursday, "a day of anger" as described by Palestinian
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
