<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1630 GMT, May 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The Pakistani military Sunday dismissed India's
claim as "rubbish and malicious" that an Indian pilot was killed
by Pakistani troops after he was captured in Kargil sector.
</P>
<P>
"The Indian claim is false, malicious, concocted and a move to
cover up its brutalities and mislead the world opinion," a
military spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that any prisoner of war, especially a pilot
is an important asset and no man of conscience could even think to
kill him.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Air Force Sunday condemned what it called the "cold-
blooded murder" of one of its pilots after he bailed out of his
crippled jet and was allegedly captured by the Pakistani army.
</P>
<P>
The body of the pilot, Squadron Leader Ajay Ahuja, which was
handed over to the Indian army by Pakistan late Friday, bore three
bullet wounds, Indian sources told journalists in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Ahuja ejected out of his Mig 21 fighter jet after it was hit by
a surface-to-air missile during airstrikes against what New Delhi
calls "infiltrators" holed up in the high reaches of the Kargil
sector in Kashmir on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is holding as a prisoner of war another Indian air
force pilot, Flight Lieutenant K. Nachiketa, who was captured
alive after ejecting from a second Mig shot down the same day. (
Pakistan-India-Pilots)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Two days after the remains of a lost Israeli
submarine were found, a senior Israeli official said on Sunday
that the submarine's sinking seemed not to be caused by an enemy
action.
</P>
<P>
Gedo Raz, head of the Israeli team searching for the submarine,
was quoted by Israel Radio as saying that initial findings showed
that the submarine might not be sank by a torpedo.
</P>
<P>
Raz added that the probable cause of sinking appeared to be a
technical malfunction or a collision with another vessel on the
water.
</P>
<P>
The submarine, named as Dakar, mysteriously disappeared with 69
sailors on board in 1968 while on its maiden voyage from Britain
to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Its remains were eventually found last Friday by a joint
American-Israeli team at a depth of 2,900 meters, between the
island of Crete and Cyprus. (Israel-Submarine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Slovakia's government candidate Rudolf Schuster was
declared winner in the country's presidential election Sunday,
ending a 15-month period of the country without a head of state.
</P>
<P>
The Central Election Commission announced that in the second
round of balloting held on Saturday, Schuster won 57.18 percent of
the vote, against won 57.18 percent of the vote garnered by rival
candidate, former prime minister Vladimir Meciar.
</P>
<P>
The voter turnout was 75.45 percent, according to the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Schuster is the leader of the Party of Civic Understanding (SOP)
and mayor of Slovakia's second city Kosice. He won the first
round of balloting on May 15.
</P>
<P>
The presidential post, which is largely ceremonial, carries a
five-year term. The inauguration is scheduled for June 15.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia has been without a president since former president
Michal Kovac's term expired in March 1998. (Slovakia-Presidential
Election) 
</P>
</TEXT>
