<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Education Ministry Seeks Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Higher Education and
 Technology of Zimbabwe has applied for a supplementary budget of
600 million Zimbabwean dollars (15 million U.S. dollars) from
treasury to meet some of its outstanding projects for the 1999
financial year.
</P>
<P>
Minister of the ministry Ignatius Chombo told the Zimbabwe News
Agency Sunday that insufficient funds had forced his ministry to
cut expenditure on some capital projects.
</P>
<P>
"We have put in a bid as we have run out, and our budget has a
shortfall of 600 million Zimbabwean dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the bulk of the supplementary budget was
needed to cover vocational training loans, capital projects and
equipment for vocational training centers.
</P>
<P>
So far 12 vocational training centers have been established,
but more are needed to cover nationwide needs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chombo hoped parliament would approve the supplementary budget
when it resumed seating in July.
</P>
<P>
Almost all government ministries have applied for supplementary
budgets barely halfway through the current financial year, the
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of the Zimbabwean dollar and the subsequent
inflation have been blamed for the seemingly financial
irresponsibility the ministries have found themselves in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
