<HEADLINE> Roundup: Abubakar Military Govt Widely Praised in Nigeria By Wang Jinyu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The former Head of State General
Abudulsalami Abubakar was widely praised in Nigeria for keeping
his promises by handing over power to democratically-elected
government on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of Agriculture Shetima Mustapha commended
General Abubakar for ensuring the success of the transition
program, and for the maintenance of peace, unity and stability in
the country during his 11- month in power, the New Nigerians
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He congratulated the out-going head of state for the successful
handing- over of power to President Olusegun Obasanjo, and called
on Nigerians to cooperate with the new government with a view to
ensuring the success of the civilian government.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Mamuda Yantumaki, gubernatorial candidate of the All
People's Party (APP) for Katsina State, expressed appreciation
to the out-going head of state for fulfilling his promise and
handing over to a civilian on May 29 as earlier scheduled.
</P>
<P>
He called on President Obasanjo to be just and fair so that
every section of the country would have a sense of belonging, and
to initiate measures that will strengthen the value of the
country's currency.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of State on Petroleum Alhaji Umaru Baba told
the media that General Abubakar had proven to Nigerians that he is
sincere and was truly committed to the return of civil rule to
the country.
</P>
<P>
Mussafir Hotel, general manager of a Total filling station,
also commended the Abubakar administration for moving the nation
forward democratically after past regimes had wasted billions of
the country's hard earned resources in executing transition to
civil rule programs.
</P>
<P>
"But the Abubakar administration during its short span of
reign, executed the shortest transition program ever in the
history of the country, he deserves commendation," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Yazid Ibrahim, a foremost member of the People's Democratic
Party (PDP) in Kaduna, said the Nigerian governments had spent
time and resources tackling political problems with total neglect
of the economy.
</P>
<P>
According to him, key macro-economic policies of government
must as a matter of urgency focus on employment creation and
protection of a process to ensure appreciation of local currency
Naira exchange rate and eradication of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Isah, secretary of Kaduna Chapter of the Keffi Old
Boys Association, said that for the first time in the history of
the country, a military man had kept faith it promises,
attributing the success of the transition to democratic rule to
the steadfastness of General Abubakar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
