<HEADLINE> 9 Killed as Taxi Crashes Into Bridge in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Nine people, including a
four-year-old boy, were killed and 11 others were injured when a
minibus taxi crashed into a bridge in southern KwaZulu-Natal
Saturday afternoon, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The taxi, carrying 19 passengers back to Wartburg from a
monthly shopping trip, crashed into the Umgeni bridge when a tire
burst.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted Road Traffic Inspectorate spokesman Colin Govender,
 who was at the scene of the accident, as saying that eight people
were flung out the taxi into the Umgeni River 20 meters below.
</P>
<P>
Five were believed to have drowned, including the four-year-old
boy, whose body was found with his head submerged between rocks,
Govender said.
</P>
<P>
Four people died from the impact of the collision and had to be
cut out of the mangled taxi.
</P>
<P>
Govender said one man's leg was amputated in the accident and,
bleeding profusely, he and the other injured victims were taken to
Grey's Hospital in Pietermaritzburg.
</P>
<P>
The driver, in his late 40s, was unable to speak because his
mouth was cut open.
</P>
<P>
He could face charges of culpable homicide, Govender said.
</P>
</TEXT>
