<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 686 Girls Rescued From Pre-Arranged Early Marriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The scheduled marriages of 686
underage girls have reportedly been cancelled in southern zone of
the Tigray regional state, the Ethiopian News Agency reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A report dispatched from Mekelle, capital of the Tigray
regional state, quoted the local women's association as saying
that the teens were rescued from settling in an early marriage, a
long time customary practice, after agreements reached among
involved parties and concerned bodies.
</P>
<P>
"The girls who were to be wed in a traditional, family-brokered
 matrimony had already cut off their schooling, awaiting their
ill-desired union," the association said.
</P>
<P>
The association had firmly stood against the marriages from
taking place with a view to preventing them from physical and
psychological health complications such connubiality would entail,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Early marriage has for long been an accepted tradition in most
rural areas in Ethiopia and is said to have been the major factor
inhibiting women's involvement in schools.
</P>
<P>
The Tigray state council had last year endorsed a family law
limiting the marriageable age at 18 and 22 respectively for girls
and men.
</P>
<P>
The number of early marriages that took place in the southern
zone of the Tigray state this year was less by 70 percent than
last year, according to the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
