<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Still Working on Release of Jailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 30 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
 Mandela is still hopeful that two Australian aid workers jailed
by a Yugoslav military court would ultimately be released, the
president's office said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Mandela was asked by former Australian
Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser to intercede on the Australians'
behalf.
</P>
<P>
Mandela then phoned Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin in an attempt to secure their
release.
</P>
<P>
The president's office Sunday declined to comment on the men's
conviction.
</P>
<P>
"The matter is still being handled. It is at a very sensitive
stage. The president is still working on it," presidential aide
Parks Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was "very much in touch" with Yeltsin and Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the president was hopeful that the Australians would
be released, Mankahlana said: "The president would not be involved
in the matter if he did not believe that."
</P>
<P>
The two men, Steve Pratt and Peter Wallace, were sentenced to
12 years and four years in prison respectively while their
Yugoslav co-worker Branko Jelen received a six-year term.
</P>
<P>
The two men were cleared of the original charge of doing
espionage for NATO, but were convicted of a new charge of passing
on information after a secret trial.
</P>
<P>
Their lawyers said an appeal would be lodged against their
conviction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
