<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Major Achievements in S.Africa's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africans will cast
their votes in the second all-race elections in the country's
history. It is believed that the ruling party of the African
National Congress (ANC) will win most of the votes in the
election.
</P>
<P>
The first all-race elections held in 1994 has put an end to the
 apartheid system which had dominated the country for 340 years,
and has started political and social transitions.
</P>
<P>
The ANC's overwhelming victory five years ago has brought the
country its first democratic constitution and the return of the
isolated nation to the world community.
</P>
<P>
All the South Africans, especially the blacks, has begun to
enjoy for the first time legal equality, citizenship and human
rights.
</P>
<P>
The national reconciliation sponsored by the ruling party has
eased the conflicts and killings between the black and the white
and also between the black dominated parties, specially between
the ruling ANC and the opposition Inkatha Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
Most people in the country have benefited from the arrival of
the democratic government and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Through its Growth, Employment and Redistribution (Gear) Plan,
the five- year-old ANC government has considerably improved the
living standard of the black people which account about 80 percent
of the country's total population.
</P>
<P>
The government's housing subsidy has made houses affordable to
some one million poor people; medical aid to underdeveloped
regions has benefited some five million people in remote and rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
Political and social transformation have peacefully resolved
all the differences over how to deal with the violent activities
in the apartheid era and successfully avoided Nuremberg-style
trial of those who committed such crimes.
</P>
<P>
Most of the South Africans and the international community have
 contributed the achievements to former ANC chief and outgoing
President Nelson Mandela, who has appointed Thabo Mbeki as his
successor.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's strong will of abandoning apartheid, sustained
efforts for democracy and his unique personality have won
popularity in home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
As a new member of the international community, South Africa
has become chairman state of the U.N. Conference on Trade and
Development, the Southern African Development Community and the
Non-Aligned Movement. It has begun to play a more and more
important role in regional and world affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to a public survey issued recently, the ANC remains
to be the most welcome party in the country. However, the
popularity of the party is by no means indicating that the future
ANC government will have plain sailing.
</P>
<P>
Violent crimes, high rate of unemployment, housing shortage
corruption and poor efficiency of the administration are the major
pressing issues facing the new government.
</P>
<P>
It is generally expected that following the June 2 elections,
Mbeki and his ANC government will in their next five-year term
contribute more to improving relations between different races and
parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
