<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, May 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Outgoing Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
Sunday confirmed reports that Israel and Syria had conducted
secret talks through various channels in the last two years,
saying progress had been made in security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
At a weekly cabinet meeting, Netanyahu said the fact that the
talks were held was itself an important achievement of his
government because Damascus had claimed that it would not enter
negotiations with Israel unless Israel first promised to withdraw
from the Golan Heights. (BC-Israel-Syria)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Sunday
sent a strong-worded message to Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud
Barak, urging him to break his silence and stop the intensified
Jewish settlement activities in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Barak is called upon to lift his silence and take steps to
stop measures taken by Netanyahu which will destroy the peace
process," said Tayeb Abdul Rahim, Secretary of PNA Chairman
Yasser Arafat, referring to outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the National Conference to Confront Settlements held
in Ramallah, Abdul Rahim also called for physical confrontation
against Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"We are called upon to translate our anger into confrontation
to stop the settlement construction," he told hundreds of
representatives of various Palestinian political factions.
(BC-Israel-Palestinians-Settlements)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Bahrain's government resigned Sunday as a prelude to
a proposed cabinet reshuffle next week, diplomatic sources in
Manama, capital of Bahrain, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Bahraini Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Isa al-Khalifa accepted the
resignation tendered by Prime Minister Sheikh Khalifa Bin Sulman
al-Khalifa, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A new government is expected to be announced by Monday.
However, no major changes will be introduced to the new
cabinet with a view to maintaining stability in the tiny island
nation. (BC-Bahrain-Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein began talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Sunday evening on the latest
developments in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah arrived in Cairo earlier in the day for a two-day
visit and went straight into the talks, also attended by senior
officials of both countries and top aides of the two
leaders, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks are expected to cover Mubarak's call for a summit
among Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians, the news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will review the coordination and consultations
among the Arab parties on the issue. (BC-Egypt-Jordan-Summit)


30/05/99 19:53 GMT

NNNN
04:01 04:01 g # PAB
</P>
