<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, May 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- NATO continues to intensify its air strikes against
Yugoslavia amid new diplomatic efforts, while more Serbian
civilians were reportedly killed during NATO's 68th day of raids.
</P>
<P>
A NATO spokesman said here on Monday that over 770 bomber
sorties were flown during the last 24 hours. It was the second
heaviest strike during the nine-week old air raids, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Yugoslav media, more than 20 civilians were
killed on Sunday in two separate attacks on a bridge and a
sanitarium. NATO confirmed that it struck a bridge in Varvarin,
central Serbia, in which at least 11 people were reportedly killed
and many others wounded.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, about 160 kilometers south of Belgrade, was
reportedly crowded with vehicles and people. Sources said the
bridge was struck twice with three missiles shortly after 1:00 p.m.
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, NATO warplanes bombed a sanitarium for the
elderly in Surdulica, southeastern Serbia, reportedly killing
about 10 civilians. (NATO-Yugoslavia-Airstrikes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has struck 24 contracts worth of 2 billion U.S.
dollars to export oil under the sixth phase of the U.N. oil-for-
food program, said Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rashid told a press conference that three Iraqi oil vessels
Monday arrived in the Turkish Jihan harbor and a fourth one will
arrive in the southern Iraqi harbor of Baker on Tuesday to
transport oil under the sixth phase of the program.
</P>
<P>
The sixth phase of the oil-for-food deal, which took effect on
May 26, allows Iraq to export 5.2 billion dollars worth of oil in
six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies
for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had demanded 600 million dollars to purchase spare parts
for the oil sector, said the minister, adding that Iraq wants to
increase its production capacity of the southern oil installations
to meet the needs of the sixth phase.(Iraq-Oil-for-food)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 13 people were charred to death and over
50 others severely injured in a devastating fire in the congested
walled city of the Capital New Delhi here Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The fire was suspected to have been triggered by a chemical
explosion as the building in which the fire broke out housed a
chemical shop, police said.
</P>
<P>
Two buildings were reduced to rubbles and two more suffered
about 60 percent damage.
</P>
<P>
Many of those caught in the fire got burnt beyond recognition
and they did not get even a fraction of a second to escape,
eyewitnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi government ordered an inquiry into the incident. (
India-Fire) 
</P>
</TEXT>
