<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uzbek, Pak Foreign Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Foreign Minister of
Uzbekistan Abdul Aziz Kamilov had two hours of talks with his
Pakistani counterpart Sartaj Aziz here on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The talks covered the entire range of bilateral matters as well
as regional issues of mutual interest with focus on the
Afghanistan issue, said a press release issued by the Pakistani
Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the immediate restoration of durable
peace in Afghanistan would bring enormous economic and commercial
benefits to the entire region, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed their "fullest support" for the promotion of an
Afghan peace process through the United Nations, the Organization
of the Islamic Conference and any other means.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers called for establishment of a
multiethnic government in Afghanistan through an indigenous
process and appealed to the international community to contribute
generously towards the reconstruction of the war-ravaged country
and the rehabilitation of the refugees, according to the press
release.
</P>
<P>
Kalimov will leave here Tuesday for Kandahar, headquarters of
the dominant Taliban militia in Afghanistan. He is expected to
urge the military leaders to attend the proposed "six plus two"
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Deputy foreign ministers from Afghanistan's six immediate
neighbors plus the United States and Russia will took part in the
meeting to discuss the peace process in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two foreign ministers also discussed
bilateral cooperation in multiple areas, including tourism,
transportation, communication, oil and gas, said the press
release.
</P>
<P>
The visit is the second tour to Pakistan for Kalimov in seven
months. The last time was in November, 1998. He will call on
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
