<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Denies Indian Allegation of Killing Its Pilot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani Foreign Ministry on
Monday categorically rejected the Indian allegation of killing its
pilot.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing here, Foreign Office spokesman
Tariq Altaf said India's accusation that its pilot, Squadron
leader Ajay Ahuja, was killed in Pakistan's custody, was
"irresponsible, offensive and motivated."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has categorically rejected the Indian allegation, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan claimed to have shot down two Indian MiG jet fighters
on May 27 which were alleged to violate the airspace in
Pakistan-administered Kashmir. One pilot was killed while the
other was captured.
</P>
<P>
The Indian side has accused Pakistan of killing the pilot, Ajay
Ahuja, in the custody. However, the spokesman categorically denied
the Indian allegation, saying that "he (the pilot) died before we
found him."
</P>
<P>
The dead body of the Indian pilot has been returned to the
Indian side.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has demonstrated full respect for and adherence to
international norms and principles applicable in such situations,"
said Altaf.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has nothing to gain from such an act as is obvious
from the fact that the other Indian Air Force pilot, Lt. K.
Nachiketa, is safe and sound and he is being treated in accordance
with established norms," he added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani troops had found the dead body of Ahuja on the
Pakistani side of the Line of Control and it was returned to the
Indian authorities without delay, said Altaf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
