<HEADLINE> People's Daily Editorial on International Children's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An editorial appears in tomorrow's
People's Daily entitled "Protecting Children and Creating a Bright
Future" for the 50th anniversary of International Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
It sends warm regards to children from all of China's ethnic
groups and to teachers and others who work for the children's
cause.
</P>
<P>
Fifty years ago, the Women's International Democratic
Federation chose June 1 as a day for children all over the world
and in December of that year, the Chinese government also
recognized it as children's day.
</P>
<P>
There are 367 million children below the age of 17 in China,
more than in any other country on earth, and the Chinese Communist
Party and government place great importance on their health and
the children's cause has made progress, the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
China prepared an Outline of the Chinese Children Development
Program in the 1990s and enacted the Law Protecting Chinese
Children, and children's survival, protection and development have
improved since the reforms and opening-up started in 1978.
</P>
<P>
But better conditions for children's survival, protection and
development are needed, the editorial says, because they are
closely related to the nation's prosperity and revitalization and
the happiness of people.
</P>
<P>
Those illegal actions that harm children need to be severely
dealt with, the editorial says, and a better education provided
for children, especially those in poor rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
