<HEADLINE> A Million Pirated CD-ROMs Destroyed In Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A million pirated CD-ROMs were
destroyed today in Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong Province,
as part of the city's efforts to make people aware of the 8th
anniversary of China's Copyright Law.
</P>
<P>
According to a Guangzhou Press and Publication Administration
official, this is the largest move taken against pirated
electronic publications in the past several years in the city.
</P>
<P>
Since June 1 of 1991 when the Copyright Law went into effect,
Guangzhou has had public gatherings to destroy pirated audio and
video publications five times and has destroyed nearly 3 million
pirated items, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase people's awareness about the law,
Guangzhou also distributed some 100,000 related pamphlets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia, South Korea Seek Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Nachagyn
Bagbandy and his visiting South Korean counterpart Kim Dae-jung
Monday expressed satisfaction over the development of bilateral
ties and pledged to achieve a new stage of growth in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy said Kim's visit was a historic event that laid the
groundwork for the two countries to develop a relationship of
complementary cooperation oriented toward the 21st century. He
said Mongolia would make full-scale efforts to expand and develop
its relationship with South Korea.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries' mutually beneficial cooperation will
benefit both countries and also contribute to the stability,
development and security in northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who arrived here Sunday on a three-day visit, said that
South Korea supports Mongolia's policy for democracy and for
developing a market economy, and will adhere to the decision to
expand and develop trade with Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
It will also support investment in Mongolia and the development
of cooperation between the two countries' businesses. It will
also provide, to the best of its ability, financial aid to
Mongolia. Kim has been the first South Korean president to visit
Mongolia since the two countries established diplomatic ties nine
years ago.
</P>
<P>
South Korea plans to provide 3.1 million U.S. dollars in free
aid to Mongolia and 19 million dollars in loans on favorable terms
from 2000 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed that both countries shared the same
stand on issues relating to security in northeast Asia and the
Asia-Pacific region. They contend that a multilateral cooperative
mechanism should be established between northeast Asian countries
to guarantee security in the region in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy expressed his understanding and support for South
Korea's efforts which are aimed at maintaining peace and stability
in the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the South Korean president also met Mongolian
Prime Minister Janlaviin Narantsatsralt and Chairman of the State
Great Hural of Mongolia Radnaasumberel Gonchigdorj.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both countries signed pacts on mutual judicial
assistance in and on the extradition of suspects as well as
agreements on educational and sports cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, South Korea has provided 14 million dollars to
Mongolia in loans on favorable terms and provides it with 200,000-
300,000 dollars in free aid annually. South Korea has become
Mongolia's fifth largest trading partner with the trade volume
hitting 74.8 million dollars in 1998. South Korean businesses
have had an investment of 14 million dollars in Mongolia so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
