<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Fertility Rate Rising in Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A new study, conducted by Olof
Akre of the Karolinska Institute in Stockholm and his colleagues,
indicates that fertility rates are actually rising, the Washington
Post said Monday.
</P>
<P>
For years some scientists have become concerned that pollution
may be causing the sperm count in men around the world to drop,
possibly threatening the fertility of the human race.
</P>
<P>
Akre and his colleagues examined birth records in Sweden
between 1983 and 1993 and found that the fertility rate had risen
over that decade.
</P>
<P>
"Much attention recently has been drawn to male reproductive
health, in part because of allegations of deteriorating sperm
quality in several populations," the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
"A decrease in male fertility cannot be ruled out on the bias
of the these results," they said. "But if present, it is minor and
totally outweighed by other favorable developments." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
