<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Better Quality Food Needed for China's Children  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese nutritionists told a
symposium here today that the country needs to make a greater
effort at developing food for children to ensure a healthy next
generation.
</P>
<P>
China has 350 million children below the age of 16, or 18.5
percent of the total number of people in the same age group in the
world and, even though things have improved, many children still
have nutrition problems.
</P>
<P>
A recent national study found that there is widespread lack of
calcium, iron, and other trace elements in children's food and
that their protein intake is insufficient. A quarter of the
children below the age of three are believed to be suffering from
rickets and 30 percent of the children below the age of five have
retarded growth.
</P>
<P>
These problems are more acute among rural children than among
urban children and this has a lot to do with food structure and
quality, according to Wang Wei, of the China Food Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
Each year, about 20 million more children are born in China and
the annual demand for powdered milk is estimated at more than 200,
000 tons, but total output is only 60,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Quality is also a problem. One study of baby formulas found
that 52.9 percent of the domestic and 70 percent of the imported
brands were up to the standard.
</P>
<P>
Choices are also quite limited for other forms of food and many
are not very scientific, Wang says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists: Better Food for Chinese Children (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nutritionists participating in the symposium said that
enterprises need to put more emphasis on developing infant formula,
milk and nutritional lunches for primary and middle school
students, and nutrition-enhanced food.
</P>
<P>
They said that there is great potential for infant food and
supplements because in spite of the fact that quite a few Chinese
industries have overproduction problems, the children's food
industry is not in that shape.
</P>
<P>
Chinese food for children is lacking both in quantity and
quality and companies need to take advantage of this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
The also asked enterprises to pay attention to the price of
children's, suggesting that reasonable is the best policy for
profits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
