<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's New President Gets First Round Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's newly sworn-in president
Olusegun Abasanjo has netted in the first round of support from
abroad and at home, Nigeria newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Secretary General, Chief Emeka Anyaoku Sunday
announced the official lifting of the suspension of Nigeria from
the organization.
</P>
<P>
He told a celebration event in Abuja Sunday that Obasanjo's
administration is not only back fully into the Commonwealth,
Nigeria's standing internationally at the United Nations, the
Organization of African Unity and all other international
organizations has also been fully restored.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank Vice President for African Region, Jean-Louis
Sabib, also said at Lagos international airport that the World
Bank would assist the new government in actualizing its economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
We know the economic situation is quite difficult in this
country. We hope to be able to help the new team that is
beginning to put the house back in order, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the much-desired relief of debts, which has amounted to 28
billion U. S. dollars, the vice president said the World Bank
would be more willing to forgive the debt of those countries that
manage their economy well, adding that, "we hope that is going to
be the case here."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman of Nigeria Labor Congress(NLC) promised
Sunday his organization will honor its promise of not launching
new strikes to assist the new government to achieve political
stability.
</P>
<P>
The NLC has successfully concluded earlier this month its
nationwide strike for 3500-Naira (about 37 U.S. dollar) minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
Among other good news for the new administration are the rising
of Naira' s value to U.S. dollar and U.S. government's promised
expanding of this year's development aid to 20 million U.S.
dollars from last year's 13 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
