<HEADLINE> Nigerian Regional Conflict Kills 50 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Ijaw and Itsekiri youths in Nigeria's
oil rich Delta region resumed their hostilities with about 50
people killed and many others injured, reported a Nigerian daily
paper.
</P>
<P>
About 88 buildings have been burnt down when the warring youths
using "sophisticated weapons" attacked the Itsekiri Village of
Aroton in Warri South West local government area of Delta State,
reported Daily Times, one of Nigeria's leading daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The youths started their assault early in the morning after
disarming security personnel in a nearby camp.
</P>
<P>
The trouble was triggered off when tax collectors from the two
council areas, which are in a hot debate over the ownership of the
area, are on their revenue drives one week ago.
</P>
<P>
Warri area is traditionally a headache for the federal
government where locals are constantly warring for land ownership
and share of oil benefit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
