<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 13 Killed in Delhi Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- At least 13 people were charred
to death and over 50 others severely injured in a devastating fire
in the congested walled city of the Capital New Delhi here Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The fire was suspected to have been triggered by a chemical
explosion as the building in which the fire broke out housed a
chemical shop, police said.
</P>
<P>
Two buildings were reduced to rubbles and two more suffered
about 60 percent damage.
</P>
<P>
Many of those caught in the fire got burnt beyond recognition
and they did not get even a fraction of a second to escape,
eyewitnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi government ordered an inquiry into the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Chief's Message Marks World No-Tobacco Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- In a message delivered to mark the "
World No-Tobacco Day" on May 31, the head of the World Health
Organization (WHO), Dr. Gro Harlem Brundtland, advised people to
give up smoking as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
"The good news is that there are real health gains to be made
from stopping at any age," Brundtland said. "Those who give up in
their early 30s enjoy a life expectancy similar to people who
never smoked. I therefore invite all smokers to take a giant step
towards better health and 'leave the pack behind'."
</P>
<P>
A recent survey in a large developing country revealed that two-
thirds of smokers mistakenly believe that smoking does little or
no harm; few are interested in quitting and fewer still have
successfully quit.
</P>
<P>
"Giving up smoking is not easy. We know that nicotine is
powerfully addictive. All of us know people who have tried to
give up smoking only to find themselves drawn back to it a few
months later," Brundtland said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a challenge for us all, and we have to rise to it
because we know that getting more smokers to quit is the key to
reducing the projected tobacco-related death toll over the next
two decades," she said.
</P>
<P>
While admitting the successful and cost-effective treatments of
nicotine replacement medicines such as nicotine gum, patches,
nasal spray and inhalers as well as non-nicotine medicines such as
bupropion, the WHO head called on manufacturers to reduce the cost
in order to bring them within the reach of smokers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO statistics, there were 1.1 billion smokers in
the world at the beginning of the 1990s, 300 million in developed
countries and 800 million in developing countries. About one-
third of the world's adults were smokers at the beginning of the
this decade, and there is little sign that this proportion has
changed substantially since.
</P>
<P>
From 1950 to 2000, WHO said, tobacco will have killed more than
60 million people in developed countries alone, more than died in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
"If current trends continue, tobacco will kill more than 100
million people in the first two decades of the 21st century,"
warned WHO. "If the current trend continues, 500 million people
alive today will be killed by tobacco." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
