<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossil Indicates Human Ancestors' Size Larger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Fossil hunters have discovered
an unusually intact pelvis bone dating back 200,000 year that is
providing new insights into how early human ancestors were shaped,
according to the Washington Post Monday.
</P>
<P>
Juan-Luis Arsuaga of the Universidad Complutense de Madrid and
colleagues unearthed the pelvis at an archaeological site in
Atapuerca, Spain.
</P>
<P>
The nearly complete male pelvis is very broad, they said. this
suggests the females had even large brains.
</P>
<P>
This would mean that the percentage of adult brain size at birth
would be higher than in modern humans, they concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
