<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cyprus Makes New Efforts for EU Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has closed its negotiations
with the European Union (EU) on 10 of the total 31 chapters under
EU considerations in its EU accession process, but it still has
long way to go before it becomes a EU member.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus concluded its recent negotiations for the European
Union (EU) membership on three more chapters, namely, consumer and
health protection, external trade relations and customs union.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government on Thursday also approved the negotiating
positions on another four chapters in the accession talks, which
cover free movement of capital, European Monetary Union, energy,
social policy which includes the thorny issue of liberalization of
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But some people warned that although Cyprus' economy was well
ahead of other applicant countries, it is still hard for the
mediterranean nation to meet EU membership standards.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU membership in 1990. Along with Slovenia,
Hungary, Poland, Estonia and the Czech Republic, Cyprus started
substantive accession negotiations with the EU in November
1998. It hopes to be admitted as an EU member by January 2003.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides for months has been holding
consultations with political party leaders in a bid to gain their
support for a package of economic reforms, in the hope that some
urgent steps can be approved by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' fiscal deficit is expected to reach 6 percent of the
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) this year, double the 3 percent
ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty. If not checked promptly,
this could endanger the future stability of the Cyprus economy and
jeopardize the accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' public debts had risen to 59.3 percent of the GDP,
dangerously approaching the 60 percent limit set by the EU.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Finance Minister Takis Clerides is planning to
present concrete proposals on measures to curb public spending,
tax rises to improve public revenue.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the value-added tax rate could be
raised to 10 percent or 11 percent from the present 8 percent this
autumn in an effort to bring it gradually up to the EU level of 15
percent by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
This would bring an additional 500 million U.S. dollars into
the state coffers, but would mean an extra 2,000 dollars to be
paid by each family as taxes.
</P>
<P>
On the semi-governmental organizations, such as the
Telecommunications, the Cyprus Airways and the Postal Service
sectors, the Cypriot government has committed itself to their
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus had initially asked for a one-year transitional period
for telecommunications after joining in the 15-nation EU, but
backed down after the EU said its request was unjustified.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' decision to withdraw the request was welcomed by the
EU, which also asked for a specific timetable from Cyprus as to
how the liberalization drive will proceed.
</P>
<P>
Clerides has also indicated that he would like to see the
parliament pass the bill removing the 9 percent ceiling on
interest rates before the summer recess. Some political figures
say the liberalization should come in 2000, others argue that it
should wait until Cyprus joins the EU.
</P>
<P>
The government enjoys no majority in the parliament and the
consent of some opposition parties is essential if any concrete
steps are to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government has also rejected the view, which is
time and again raised by some EU countries, that it is not in a
position to guarantee future fulfillment of the chapters of the
acquisition of communications in the whole island.
</P>
<P>
The government insists that there has been no link between the
accession process and the island's political issue. It believes
that the accession will be the catalyst to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus had been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Civilian Deaths and Injuries as NATO Intensifies Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS,May 31 (Xinhua) -- NATO continues to intensify its
air strikes against Yugoslavia amid new diplomatic efforts, while
more Serbian civilians were reportedly killed during NATO's 68th
day of raids.
</P>
<P>
A NATO spokesman said here on Monday that over 770 bomber
sorties were flown during the last 24 hours. It was the second
heaviest strike during the nine-week old air raids, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Yugoslav media, more than 20 civilians were
killed on Sunday in two separate attacks on a bridge and a
sanitarium. NATO confirmed that it struck a bridge in Varvarin,
central Serbia, in which at least 11 people were reportedly killed
and many others wounded.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, about 160 kilometers south of Belgrade, was
reportedly crowded with vehicles and people. Sources said the
bridge was struck twice with three missiles shortly after 1:00 p.m.
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, NATO warplanes bombed a sanitarium for the
elderly in Surdulica, southeastern Serbia, reportedly killing
about 10 civilians.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, two local people, a bus driver and an
interpreter were killed and three foreign journalists were wounded
by NATO bombs while traveling by bus. The journalists were from
Britain, France and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Britain on Monday asked the Red Cross to visit London Times
newspaper journalist Ere-Ann Prentice, who was injured during the
NATO air raid in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
