<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Oil Minister on Sixth Phase of Oil-for-Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has struck 24 contracts worth
of 2 billion U.S. dollars to export oil under the sixth phase of
the U.N. oil-for-food program, said Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Mohammed Rashid on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rashid told a press conference that three Iraqi oil vessels
Monday arrived in the Turkish Jihan harbor and a fourth one will
arrive in the southern Iraqi harbor of Baker on Tuesday to
transport oil under the sixth phase of the program.
</P>
<P>
The sixth phase of the oil-for-food deal, which took effect on
May 26, allows Iraq to export 5.2 billion dollars worth of oil in
six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies
for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had demanded 600 million dollars to purchase spare parts
for the oil sector, said the minister, adding that Iraq wants to
increase its production capacity of the southern oil installations
to meet the needs of the sixth phase.
</P>
<P>
Under the fourth and fifth phases of the program, Iraq was
allowed to purchase 300 million dollars worth of oil spare parts
in each phase for its dilapidated oil facilities.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq has long accused the U.S. and British
representatives in the U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking the
approval of its contracts concluded for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said that only 14 million dollars worth of contracted
oil spare parts under the fourth phase have arrived in Iraq and
none under the fifth phase has reached the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was reluctant to agree to renew the oil-for-food deal,
worrying that the U.S. and Britain are trying to make the
deal an alternative to the lifting of sanctions imposed on the
country in 1990 following its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
