<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Flies to France for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid left here on Monday for Paris on a four-day visit to
France.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before departure, Abdel-Meguid said that
he will meet with French President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin and Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
Arab League sources said that Abdel-Meguid will discuss with
French leaders and senior officials how to coordinate the
Arab-French-European efforts to help push the Middle East peace
process forward.
</P>
<P>
Little progress has been made in the peace process since 1996
due to the intransigent policies adopted by Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Hopes of reviving the Arab-Israeli peace talks increased after
moderate Ehud Barak, leader of Israel's opposition Labor Party,
defeated Netanyahu in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid will also tackle with the French side the
situation in Iraq and the need to relieve the hardship of the
Iraqi people, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under crippling economic sanctions imposed by the
United Nations Security Council in 1990 after its invasion of
Kuwait. The country is in urgent need of food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The talks will also cover means of promoting the Arab-French
ties, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
France, which desires to play a key role in resolving Mideast
issues, keeps close contacts with Arab countries and the 22-nation
pan-Arab forum.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League chief traveled to Paris at an invitation of
the Arab World Institute there on the occasion of a book fair,
which will hold a seminar on a book written by him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
