<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Total Deposits for April Increase in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Total deposits in Hong Kong grew
by 1.7 percent to 48.8 billion HK dollars (6.25 billion U.S.
dollars) in April this year, according to statistics released by
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) here Monday.
</P>
<P>
HK dollar and foreign currency deposits registered increases of
1.9 percent and 1.3 percent respectively. The proportion of HK
dollar deposits to total deposits increased from 57 percent at end-
March to 57.2 percent at end-April.
</P>
<P>
The rise in HK dollar deposits reflected the respective gains
of 5.1 percent and 1 percent in savings and time deposits during
the month.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, demand deposits dropped by 0.4 percent,
probably due to the high base of comparison in March in connection
with increased treasury deposits for tax rebates.
</P>
<P>
Foreign currency deposits rose by 1.3 percent in April, with
both U.S. dollar deposits and non-U.S. dollar foreign currency
deposits increasing at the same rate.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures also show that total loans and advances
shrank for the sixth consecutive month, by 1.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
In line with the slowdown of economic activity in the region,
loans for use outside Hong Kong declined by 0.8 percent, while
domestic loans fell by 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The HK dollar loan-to-deposit ratio decreased to 96.7 percent
at the end of April, as against 99.2 percent at the end of March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
