<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Measures in Place for S. African Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
has made sufficient security arrangements to ensure a free and
fair election, Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi, who chairs an inter-ministerial election security
committee, said about 100,000 police officers and soldiers would
be deployed on June 2, the election day, supported by 100 aircraft
and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that there would be no call for the use of
this personnel, except in exceptional circumstances," Mufamadi
said.
</P>
<P>
He said unregistered voters would not be allowed to enter
voting stations Wednesday in order to preempt disruptions at
voting points, as it had all along been made clear that one had to
be registered to take part in the election.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready and sufficiently organized to ensure that nobody
is going to interfere with the voting process," Mufamadi said,
adding that extra security staff would be deployed at trouble
spots.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey indicated that between three and four million
unregistered citizens intended to turn up at voting stations to
try to cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said the country was experiencing a normal, peaceful
political process in the past weeks despite some incidents of
violence. About 775 political gatherings, rallies and marches had
so far been successfully secured, he said.
</P>
<P>
Two people were shot and wounded and a third was stabbed with a
knife Sunday when supporters of the African National Congress
(ANC) and the United Democratic Movement (UDM) clashed at a UDM
rally at Khayelitsha outside Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The UDM claimed that Saturday ANC supporters shot dead a UDM
member and wounded others in Esikhawini township in northern
KwaZulu-Natal. But the ANC denied it.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said the incidents were under investigation.
</P>
<P>
He said his committee undertook numerous visits to provinces in
the past week, and met at least twice a week to coordinate
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"Intelligence and operational information have been and are
being updated on a daily basis. On the whole we don't see serious
problems facing the voters on election day," Mufamadi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African New MPs to Be Sworn in Under New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The swearing-in of parliament
members (MPs) elected in Wednesday's general election would, for
the first time, be done in terms of South Africa's new
constitution, National Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Constitutional Court President Judge Arthur Chaskalson would
preside at the ceremony, to be held in the National Assembly
chamber on the morning of June 14, South African Press Association
quoted Ginwala as saying.
</P>
<P>
MPs would be inducted in batches of 10, and take the oath in
their language of choice, she told a media briefing at parliament.
</P>
<P>
They would then elect a new speaker, who would in turn preside
over the election of a deputy speaker.
</P>
<P>
Ginwala smiled when asked whether she would be available for
re-election as speaker, saying it was up to the African National
Congress' national executive committee as to who the party's
candidate would be.
</P>
<P>
She said President Nelson Mandela, who remains in office until
a new president is inaugurated in Pretoria on June 16, would be at
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The assembly would then adjourn for lunch, after which it would
re- convene and elect, again under Chaskalson's supervision, a new
president -- by all indications set to be ANC leader and current
Deputy President of the country, Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of all parties would make short speeches, and the new
president would also address the House.
</P>
<P>
MPs would return to Parliament on June 20 for training and
orientation programs.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the new National Council of Provinces (NCOP) would
be sworn in on June 24.
</P>
<P>
The nine provincial legislatures are to meet on June 15 to
elect premiers and permanent delegates to the NCOP, presided over
by judges assigned by the province's judge-presidents.
</P>
<P>
Ginwala said suggestions were that the new premiers be
inaugurated on June 18.
</P>
<P>
Parliament -- consisting of the National Assembly and the NCOP
-- would meet for the first time on June 25, when the new
president would deliver a state-of-the-nation address.
</P>
<P>
This would be debated by the National Assembly on June 28 and
29, with the president set to reply on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Parliament would then adjourn until sometime in August, Ginwala
said.
</P>
<P>
The length of this session would have to be determined by the
new Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Ginwala said a gap had been discovered in the new constitution
-- no provision was made for when the term of Parliament's
presiding officers should end, whereas it stated cabinet ministers
remain in office until the new cabinet is constituted.
</P>
<P>
Parliament would then in effect be run by the secretary to
parliament, Sindiso Mfenyana.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question, Mfenyana said it was anticipated that
about a third of the newly-elected MPs would be newcomers to
Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
