<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive on Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Environment is not a cost for
doing business, but a real opportunity to improve business, Tung
Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the Private Sector Committee on the
Environment Annual Business and Environment Conference, Tung said
improving the environment is being put at the center of the
government's policies from 1999 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that it stays that way for every year
of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"I will do that because I am convinced that there is tremendous
opportunity for Hong Kong in improving our environment," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung noted that individual companies have found that
opportunity in reducing their costs by greater efficiency in the
use of power and materials, cutting down on waste and emissions
and increasing productivity.
</P>
<P>
For Hong Kong as a whole, he said the opportunities come
through improving the quality of the living environment for every
citizen.
</P>
<P>
After reviewing the progress that Hong Kong has made in
improving the environment, Tung said much more remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
It needs to improve Hong Kong's waste management system,
develop its sewage system further and tackle problems with urban
air pollution, he said.
</P>
<P>
The primary responsibility for the government is to lead that
process of change.
</P>
<P>
"One of our most important tasks for the next decade is going
to be building up institutions and programs with our neighbors in
Guangdong for regional cooperation to tackle common problems of
pollution and environmental pressure," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said it also needs to increase public
understanding and build more effective partnerships as a community
to respond to these pressures successfully.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that street level air pollution is the most pressing
environmental issue that Hong Kong faces today.
</P>
<P>
For the present, the task is to achieve much greater
cooperation and coordination between transport operators, oil
companies, the motor vehicle trade and the government, so that
best available technologies and practices are introduced rapidly,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
