<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Gemstone Exports Exceed $8mln </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's change in policies
has greatly driven up exports of gemstones, the Deputy Minister of
Energy and Minerals, Manju Msambya, has said.
</P>
<P>
The country earned 8.127 million U.S. dollars from exports of
gemstones in 1998, compared with 200,000 U.S. dollars 11 years ago
when large quantities were smuggled out of the country, media
reports on Monday quoted Msambya as saying.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister made the remarks Sunday at the seventh
Tanzania Mineral Dealers Development Association (TAMIDA) show in
the northern town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, the country started to issue licences to dealers
allowing them to engage in the gemstone business, thus ending the
state-monopoly era when all minerals were marketed through a
single enterprise, he said.
</P>
<P>
Exports of gemstones have climbed up steadily thanks to the
liberalization of the trade. In 1990, exports of gemstones reached
1.584 million U.S. dollars while in 1995 the figure further rose
to 6.46 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The figures demonstrate the role of the private mineral
dealers in supporting our policies and commitments," the deputy
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Msambya said Tanzania is endowed with vast mineral resources
including gemstones found nearly all over the country.
</P>
<P>
There is increasing evidence that the potential is much bigger
than the government has anticipated as new finds are being made
time and again.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is taking measures including devising
special incentives to develop gemstone, gold and other mineral
resources in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the show, to be closed Monday, is aimed at giving
dealers an opportunity to buy gemstones directly from the source
and not through smugglers in neighboring countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
