<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Allied Forces In DRC To Fight On: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mugabe said this at Ndjili airport in Kinshasa Sunday where he
stopped over from General Olusegun Obasanjo's inauguration in
Nigeria, to address about 200 Zimbabwean soldiers fighting
alongside the Congolese army and its other allies from Angola,
Chad and Namibia, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to reports that Rwanda planned to move its
forces from eastern Congo and that Uganda intended to honor its
Libyan brokered peace deal with DRC.
</P>
<P>
"Let that demonstration be practical on the ground. If it is
not practical it should not be believed," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He said the new Nigerian leadership supported the allied forces
in the DRC, as they were there in the same spirit of preserving
fellow African countries' sovereignty as Nigeria itself did in
Liberia and Sierra Leone under the west African peace-keeping
force, ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Despite loss of life of its soldiers, Mugabe said Zimbabwe
received honor and respect for assisting countries in conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Yes it means suffering but sacrifices must be made," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said the allied forces were willing to discuss
peace and in that regard he had asked Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni to establish the truth of Rwanda's declaration of a
unilateral peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
