<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profiles of S. African Election Contenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are profiles of
five leading contenders in the 2nd all-race elections set for June
2.
</P>
<P>
-- Thabo Mbeki
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, as President of the ruling African National Congress
(ANC), was appointed successor to the outgoing President Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He was born on June 18, 1942 in Idutywa, Queenstown where he
spent his childhood. He began participating in students strikes
against apartheid when he studied in high school.
</P>
<P>
He completed his British A levels exams between 1960 and 1961,
and obtained a master of economics degree from Sussex University
in 1966. Mbeki joined the ANC Youth League in 1956 and was
elected president of the African Students Association in 1962.
</P>
<P>
He worked in the ANC offices in London, Britain from 1967 to
1970 and later underwent military training in the then Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
He served in the ANC's Revolutionary Council as assistant
secretary in Lusaka, Zambia in 1971.
</P>
<P>
In late 1980, Mbeki, as a senior ANC official, participated in
series of talks that led to the adoption of the interim
constitution for the new South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Mbeki was elected Chairman of the ANC. And in 1997, he
was elected ANC president.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has been South Africa's deputy president since 1994.
</P>
<P>
-- Mangosuthu Buthelezi
</P>
<P>
President of Inkatha Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi is currently the Home Affairs Minister, chairman of
the House of Traditional Leaders in KwaZulu Natal Province and
Traditional Prime Minister of the Zulu People after he became a
member of parliament in April 1994.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi, born in Mahlabathini on August 27, 1928, traces his
ancestry back to King Shaka, founder of the Zulu nation.
</P>
<P>
He studied in primary school and high school between 1933 and
1943, and matriculated at Adams College in Amanzimtoti in 1947 and
obtained a Bachelor of Arts degree from Fort Hare University in
1950.
</P>
<P>
He was made the KwaZulu Legislative Assembly's chief executive
officer in 1972, and became Kwazulu's chief minister from 1976 to
1994, South African Home Affairs Minister in 1994, and he has been
appointed acting president by President Nelson Mandela on a number
of occasions.
</P>
<P>
-- Marthinus van Schalkwyk
</P>
<P>
Leader of the New National Party.
</P>
<P>
Van Schalkwyk was born on November 10, 1959, and matriculated
at Pietersburg High School, Northern Province, in 1977.
</P>
<P>
He went for military service for two years from 1978. He
obtained Bachelor and Master degrees of Political Science at the
Rand Afrikaans University in Johannesburg. He once studied law in
Britain and other European countries. He married to Suzette. They
have a son, Christiaan.
</P>
<P>
He was elected a member of parliament for the then National
Party (NP) for Randburg, Johannesburg, in November 1990. He became
the NP's media director for the party's 1994 election campaign and
later became a member of the Parliamentary Portfolio Committee on
Communications.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Van Schalkwyk was appointed to the NP's Gauteng
Province Executive Committee and Federal Council. He became the
NP's executive director in 1997 and was elected as the party's
national leader on September 9, 1997 after FW de Klerk stepped
down.
</P>
<P>
-- Anthony James Leon
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Born on December 15, 1956, Leon obtained his Bachelor of Arts
and Bachelor of Law degrees from Wits University where he was the
president of the Law Students' Council and the vice-president of
the Unviersity's Students Representative Council.
</P>
<P>
He was the co-chairman of the Constitutional Assembly Theme
Committee on Fundamental Rights from 1994 to 1996, and adviser
during the Convention for a Democratic South Africa from 1989 to
1994.
</P>
<P>
He was an attorney of the Supreme Court of South Africa and a
lecturer at law at Wits University and a trustee of the Drive
Alive Foundation from 1991 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
-- Bantu Holomisa
</P>
<P>
President of the United Democratic Movement (UDM).
</P>
<P>
Holomisa, the former military leader of the black Homeland of
Transkei, co-founded the UDM in 1997 with Roelf Meyer, formerly a
leading National Party member, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Holomisa was the Deputy Minister of Environmental Affairs and
Tourism before his expulsion from the ruling African National
Congress.
</P>
<P>
He was the Commander of the Transkei Defense Force and head of
the Transkei government until the inaugural democratic elections
in 1994 when he was chosen by the ANC's election committee to
campaign nationally.
</P>
<P>
Holomisa, who is one of the first two black persons to be
accepted by the South African Army College for a year-long senior
staff officers' course, is an able athlete who has played rugby,
soccer and tennis.
</P>
<P>
He was the parliamentary rugby squads vice-captain from 1994 to
1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> an Overview </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's second
democratic election is to be held Wednesday, June 2. Following is
a brief introduction to this event:
</P>
<P>
The election is generally believed to be a foregone conclusion,
with the ruling African National Congress (ANC) expected to retain
its power. At stake, however, is whether the ANC would win a
two-thirds majority as it has been craving for, and which party
would be the new official opposition.
</P>
<P>
Elections for the National Assembly and provincial legislatures
would be held on the same day. That is to say, a voter has to cast
two ballots, one for the national legislature, the other for the
provincial legislature in his/her province.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly will have 400 seats and a provincial
legislature will have between 30 and 80 seats depending on the
population of the province.
</P>
<P>
Of the 400 seats in the National Assembly, 200 will be filled
by candidates on the national lists of political parties and the
remaining 200 will be taken by candidates on
provincial-to-national lists in order to ensure provincial
representation.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, if a political party contests the election on both
national and provincial levels, it should have three separate
lists of candidates: the national list, the provincial-to-national
list and the provincial list(s). The provincial lists of
candidates are for provincial legislatures only.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen political parties are going to take part in the
national election, while 10 others will contest on the provincial
level.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is using an electoral system called proportional
representation. Under the system, the representation a party
receives in a legislature is in proportion to the percentage of
votes it receives in the election. For instance, if a party wins
70 percent of the vote, it will have 70 percent of seats in the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Another major electoral system is the constituency-based
"first-past-the- post" system. Under such a system, each
constituency has a seat in parliament and the candidate who
receives the most votes in the constituency gets the seat in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has a population of 40.6 million, with about 22.8
million of them as eligible voters. More than 18 million of the
voters have registered for the election.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, a total of 15,000 polling stations manned by
250,000 electoral officials will be open from 7 a.m. (0500 GMT)
until 9 p.m. (1900 GMT) across the country. The voting process
will also be watched by political party agents and international
observers.
</P>
<P>
Some 90,000 security personnel including defense force soldiers
will be deployed across the country and certain "high-risk" areas
will be heavily guarded.
</P>
<P>
Provisional results of the poll will be available Thursday and
the final results will be announced by the Independent Electoral
Commission within a week of the election.
</P>
<P>
The new National Assembly will have its first session on June
14 and the new president will be elected by members of parliament
on the same day.
</P>
<P>
The new president will be sworn in on June 16 in Pretoria at a
ceremony attended by thousands of dignitaries, including quite a
number of heads of state.
</P>
<P>
Since the ANC is set to win the election, its president, Thabo
Mbeki, currently state deputy president, will be the successor to
the revered outgoing president Nelson Mandela.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
