<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia to withdraw from Jezzine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army
(SLA) Monday announced it would formally start withdrawal from the
town of Jezzine in south Lebanon on Tuesday and will complete it
within 10 to 15 days.
</P>
<P>
The plan was announced by the militia's commander Antoine Lahd
in a news conference held in Marjayoun inside the Israeli-occupied
border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Jezzine, the largest Christian town in south Lebanon, is
outside the border zone but has been under SLA control since 1985.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-member SLA was trained and paid by Israeli forces to
help them patrol the security zone which the Jewish state set up
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Due to rising casualties resulting from Lebanese guerrillas'
bombings, the militia last week decided to withdraw the 170-man
garrison from Jezzine into the Israeli occupied enclave.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, a Shiite Muslim group, is leading a
guerrilla war to oust Israeli occupation troops and SLA out of the
country. It gets financial and political support from both Syria
and Iran.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier statement, Lahd expressed hope that the Labanese
authorities take over Jezzine after the SLA departure.
</P>
<P>
There are fears among the Christian population that Hezbollah
guerrillas will enter the town and seek revenge on suspected
collaborators with Israel, a claim that has been denied by the
group's leader Sayyed Hasan Nasrallah at a mass rally on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses from Jezzine said SLA militiamen had knocked down
earth mounds and dynamited fortified positions after packing arms
and ammunition onto waiting trucks from Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Truck convoys were also seen streaming out of the town,
carrying artillery and mortar guns, equipment, ammunition and
household furniture to Marjayoun, the SLA's headquarters inside
the border enclave.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that among the militiamen in Jezzine, around
70 have decided to stay in the town to place their fate in the
hands of the authorities.
</P>
<P>
A parliament member from Jezzine has urged the Lebanese
government to pass an amnesty on SLA fighters, most of them he
said are forced to join the group for financial reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
