<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Says Cox Report Is Like Hollywood Movie Script </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official has
suggested that the U.S.'s Cox Report should have been made into a
movie in Hollywood with a disclaimer at the beginning, saying "
this is pure fiction."
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here this afternoon, Zhao Qizheng,
director of the Information Office of the State Council, commented
on the May 25 report, saying that China has never stolen secrets
from the U.S. nuclear weapons lab, as it claims. Zhao showed
Chinese and foreign journalists pictures and technological
instructions on W79, W87, W88, and the F-117A Nighthawk that were
from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"An ordinary Chinese or American without much knowledge about
the military might find all this data on warheads surprising,"
Zhao, once a senior engineer, told Xinhua, "but, in fact the
information is open to the public in the United States and anyone
who has access to the Internet can get it."
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that the Cox Report is a fabrication for people who
are not insiders about someone who just sneaked into some Taiwan-
based connection of the Central Intelligence Agency's, opened a
safe, and took the classified documents about W87 or W88.
</P>
<P>
"This is like something out of the James Bond series," he said.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, an engineer from the China Internet Information
Center showed the journalists how to get at these so-called
secrets on the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
