<HEADLINE> Trial of Kurdish Rebel Leader Begins in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Ankara State Security
Court No. 2 on Monday started trial of PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan
on Imrali Island in Marmara Sea near Turkey's western province of
Bursa.
</P>
<P>
The court rejected a request of Ocalan's lawyers to postpone
the case before the trial started.
</P>
<P>
Intervenors and spectators were permitted to enter the court
hall, and only correspondents of Turkey's State Radio and
Television Corporation and Anatolian News Agency got the privilege
to take pictures in the hall.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was brought to the court hall from the prison and was
taken into a bullet-proof glass case in the hall.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan pleaded for his life in the court, saying "I would like
to state my determination to work for peace and brotherhood within
the democratic republic" if he could avoid the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to point out that I will live for peace and
brotherhood and be in the service of the Republic of Turkey for
the materialization of this purpose," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I promise that I will work to stop this bloodshed and for
peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has beefed up security measures in the
court hall and the whole Imrali Island.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan faces the death penalty in the case filed in the Ankara
State Security Court that accused him of being responsible for the
14-year-long Kurdish struggle for independence which claimed over
37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was arrested by special Turkish agents in Kenya in
mid-February when he left the Greek Embassy in Nairobi, where he
had taken refuge for 12 days after an undisclosed odyssey seeking
asylum in vain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
