<HEADLINE> Kuerten Sails to Quarters in French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Eighth seed Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil
booked his quarterfinal ticket at the French Open here on Monday
by defeating Bohdan Ulihrach of the Czech Republic in straight
sets.
</P>
<P>
After losing the opening three games, Kuerten who the title in
1997, recovered to win the competition 6-4, 6-4, 6-2 in just one
hour 38 minutes against the 40th-ranked Ulihrach whom Kuerten also
beat on his way to the title in Monte Carlo last month.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten took the first set in 32 minutes and nine minutes more
for the second set before surging ahead 4-1 in the third set after
Ulihrach, who has equalled his best Grand Slam showing by reaching
the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian is hoping to earn the top spot in the world
rankings as well as recapture the title he won two years ago, and
said he thought he was currently playing some of the best tennis
of his life.
</P>
<P>
"I've learned a lot on the Tour, particularly how to relax on
the big points," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Kuerten has been in superb form on European
clay this season, having captured titles at Monte Carlo and Rome,
and has had a relatively easy run to the last 16 without playing
anyone ranked in the top 30.
</P>
<P>
He will now meet either Arnaud Di Pasquale of France or Andrei
Medvedev of Ukraine in Wednesday's quarter-finals. 
</P>
