<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Says Smoking Controls Still Difficult </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing talked
today about the government's role in controlling tobacco use and
called for stronger measures to curb smoking.
</P>
<P>
Smoking control is a tough task because smoking among young
people and women is on the rise, Li said in a written speech for a
national seminar for World No-Tobacco Day.
</P>
<P>
Even though there has been some success in this over the past
20 years, he said, governments at all levels should make smoking
control their responsibility.
</P>
<P>
China's 320 million smokers make it the world's largest
cigarette consumer and it probably has the largest number of
victims.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Health show that the number of
smokers in China increased 3.74 percentage points in the 1984-1996
period and the mortality rate of lung cancer, which is believed to
be a result of smoking, rose 4.5 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang acknowledges that China faces
a problem with smoking among teenagers and women, adding that
there is a particular challenge from tobacco companies in certain
developed countries, who have been condemned in their own
countries, but attempt to promote their products in developing
countries like China by luring young people.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry is considering more legislation and
education to stop smoking among young people. Schools need to be a
smoke-free environment for some 200 million students, he says, and
government and medical personnel and teachers should be models in
saying 'No' to tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry and the Chinese Association on Smoking and Health,
the country's leading anti-smoking organization, have encouraged
85 cities to put a ban on smoking in public places. Advertising of
tobacco products is being phased out in major cities.
</P>
<P>
World No-Tobacco Day is designed to increase awareness of the
impact of smoking on people's health, according to Dr. Edward
Hoekstra, who is in charge of the World Health Organization's
China office.
</P>
<P>
This year, it deals not only with the need for preventive
measures and emphasizes the importance of programs to stop smoking,
he says, adding that its theme "Leave the pack behind" speaks for
itself.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
