<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke053139 -View Security in All Aspects, Says Malaysian Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Security in the Asia Pacific
region should encompass all aspects of the fundamental needs, core
values and vital interests of the society and the state, and not
confined to security in military terms, said Malaysian Deputy
Prime Minister Datuk Seri Abdullah Ahmad Badawi.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, there was a need to shift the narrow
preoccupation with military security to a wider concern for
comprehensive security.
</P>
<P>
"When we begin to see our security in such comprehensive terms,
the logic of cooperating for mutual security in an interdependent
world will become even more persuasive and compelling," he said in
his keynote address at the 13th Asia-Pacific Roundtable here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day roundtable themed "Confidence Building and
Conflict Reduction" was attended by some 100 participants and
observers from 19 countries. It is jointly organized by the
Malaysian Institute of Strategic and International Studies (Isis)
and the ASEAN-Isis.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Malaysia believed that the peaceful pursuit of
security and the pacific settlement of disputes in the region
would be greatly enhanced if states regard security as a mutual,
common and an indivisible matter.
</P>
<P>
He also said that differences and conflicts of interests do not
have to degenerate into violent confrontations and be resolved, if
at all, by force.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also noted that without mutual cooperation, the
integrating forces of technology, information, trade, investment,
finance and tourism among the states would not be possible.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the economic turmoil that hit many nations in the
region, including Malaysia, Abdullah said that although the
measures taken to overcome the crisis seemed to be working well,
Malaysia was fully committed to completing the agenda it had set
for itself in its national economic recovery plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects Good Summer Grain Harvest Despite Drought (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
North China's Hebei Province has established a good foundation
for increased wheat output by introducing new varieties of high
quality wheat. Local farmers are busy harvesting wheat on some 2.7
million hectares.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Chinese Ministry of Agriculture recently
noted a slight decrease in the area sown to summer grain has
decreased slightly on last year to an estimated 112 million
hectares, However, he said, the output of summer grain, mainly
wheat, is expected to rise slightly on last year.
</P>
<P>
Wu Hongyao, an agricultural expert, attributed this year's
increased output of summer grain to the alleviation of drought
conditions during the winter, as well as intensified management
over wheat fields and expanded efforts to fight drought,
preventing and alleviating plant diseases and insect pests, the
application of practical agro-techniques for larger areas of
farmland and successful adjustments to growing summer grain.
</P>
<P>
The total area sown to summer grain has decreased, but the
coverage of high quality wheat has increased significantly and is
considered to be an important factor leading to the increased
wheat output. Related efforts have further demonstrated the
initial success of using science and technology to promote
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
China has earmarked five million yuan this year to finance
activities related to using science and technology to advance
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China has launched a large-scale campaign to
build farmland irrigation facilities in recent years along with
the introduction various other measures, including policies to
increase the income of farmers, have played important role in
raising the wheat output.
</P>
<P>
China harvested 113.1 billion kg of summer grain in 1998, down
11 percent on 1997. The former figure yet accounted for some 25
percent of the country's total 1998 grain output of 490 million
tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects Good Summer Grain Harvest Despite Drought (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Information from China's major
summer grain production bases show that the country has overcome
the combination of record summer flooding in 1998 and one of the
worst droughts in history and will achieve a good summer grain
harvest this year.
</P>
<P>
China not only suffered from scarce rainfall between last
autumn and this spring, but also withstood the warmest winter in
50 years. A dozen provinces and autonomous regions in the Yellow
and Huaihe river valleys, and in both north and west China were
hit by a drought spell which adversely affected close to a third
of winter crops.
</P>
<P>
Record summer flooding in 1998 continues to affect cultivation
in some areas. The floods not only killed 3,004 people, but also
inundated 21 million ha of farmland, destroyed nearly five million
homes and caused economic losses of some 166.6 billion yuan (about
20.8 billion U.S. dollars) in their wake.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, one of the country's leading agricultural provinces,
suffered through the worst drought in 80 years. "Shandong has
stabilized cultivated areas and anticipates a good wheat harvest
which is expected to remain at last year's level of some 20
billion kilograms," according to Deputy Governor Chen Yanming who
is in charge of agricultural and rural work.
</P>
<P>
East China's Anhui Province expects to harvest eight billion kg
of summer grain, up 30 percent on last year's level.
</P>
<P>
An agricultural official from Henan, now China's most populous
province, said the province witnessed the worst drought since
meteorological records have been kept, but nonetheless planted 4.9
million hectares of wheat and allocated over 500 million yuan for
related protection efforts.
</P>
<P>
The official predicted that this year's total wheat output will
exceed last year's level.
</P>
<P>
Li Maozheng, a farmer from Xiejiying Township in Henan, said: "
Our village has about 206 ha of farmland and 108 wells. The
drought had little effect on farmland and I expect a good wheat
harvest."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
