<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ITU to Set Mobile Telephone Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Major differences between operators
and manufacturers may prevent the establishment of a unified
worldwide cellular telephone system in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Bargaining covering the harmonization of the major
technological families in the third or latest generation of mobile
telecommunications entered one of the most challenging stages at
today's opening session of the International Telecommunications
Union (ITU) in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The 17th meeting of the ITU's Task Force 8/1 will feature
discussions and decisions related to detailed standards for the
code-division multiple-access (CDMA) mobile telephone system.
</P>
<P>
However, economic interests rather than technological
terminology will be the top concern of the 200-plus participants
from 25 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
CDMA technologies used in the United States is different
significantly from those used in Japan and Europe.
Telecommunications manufacturers and operators from related sides
are trying to persuade ITU to incorporate more of their
technologies in the global standard.
</P>
<P>
A Motorola official, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
said it will save manufacturers substantial costs related to
patent fees.
</P>
<P>
Eiji Kito from Japan-based Nippon Electric Corp. (NEC) said
that the harmonization of CDMA technological standards will
greatly enhance the position of his company's products in
international market.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunication operators, on the other hand, insist the
existing cellular telephone network should be valid under the new
global standards due to their heavy investments in related
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Satellite mobile telecommunications companies such as ICO,
Globalstar and Iridium are also closely following the evolution of
CDMA technology.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, ITU TG8/1 Chairman Michael
Callendar said that the ITU may decide the unification of CDMA
technological standards in two phases.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources noted that the first phase will include the
establishment of regional technological blocs, such as the Europe-
based 3GPP and the U.S.-based 3GPP2.
</P>
<P>
The second phase will center on the harmonization of the
technological standards in several regions.
</P>
<P>
Japan is pressing hard for unified global standards on CDMA
technology and will begin the full-scale commercial application of
CDMA in 2001.
</P>
<P>
China is also supporting the harmonization of CDMA technology
and has submitted a candidate CDMA standard to the ITU. Sources
say that China and Europe are discussing the possibility of
combing the technological standards of both sides in the near
future. Chinese CDMA equipment will gain wider access to the
international market if the proposal meets with success.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing meeting of the ITU will conclude on June 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Records Trade Surplus of 1.63b U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a trade
surplus of 6.2 billion ringgit (about 1.63 billion U.S. Dollars)
in April this year compared with 3.4 billion ringgit (about 0.9
billion dollars) in the same month last year, the Statistics
Department announced here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was the 18th consecutive month since November 1997 that
Malaysia chalked up a surplus, thanks to higher exports versus
imports, the department said in its preliminary release of the
Malaysian External Trade Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew by 16.4 percent or 3.7 billion ringgit (0.97
billion dollars) to 25.975 billion ringgit (6.8 billion dollars)
while imports increased by only 4.4 percent or 900 million ringgit
(236.8 million dollars) to 19.729 billion ringgit (5.19 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of 1999, the trade surplus was higher
at 22 billion ringgit (5.8 billion dollars) from a surplus of 12.5
billion ringgit (3.28 billion dollars) in the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
The department said that full details of the trade figures
would be published sometime in the first week of June 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
