<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Meets Senior Argentine Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian said here today that the Chinese people cannot be bullied
and any attempt to threaten or blackmail the nation is doomed to
failure.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who also serves concurrently as vice-chairman of the
Central Military Commission and state councilor, made the remarks
during a meeting Carlos Maria Zabala, the Joint Chief of Staff of
Argentina's Armed Forces and the Chief of Staff of the Navy of
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Chi said China and Argentina are important countries in Asia
and Latin America. He pointed to the smooth development of
bilateral relations and noted the increasing frequency of high-
level exchange visits since the two countries established
diplomatic ties some 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said the development of the relations between the two
nations and their armed forces conforms to the fundamental
interest of the people in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the Argentine government for cooperating with China
in the realm of international affairs and expressed gratitude for
its support for China's reunification effort and adherence to the
"one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Chi pointed to the fact that China was invaded and robbed
throughout modern history and noted that the Chinese people highly
value independence and freedom acquired through the devotion and
sacrifice of previous generations.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China has worked to build the new
international political and economic order since the end of the
Cold War, and noted the recent resurgence of hegemonism.
</P>
<P>
Chi addressed the U.S.-led NATO strikes against Yugoslavia, a
sovereign state, and the May 8th bombing of the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade. He stressed that "the Chinese people will not accept"
the views of U.S. congressmen who have insisted on the Cold War
mentality created the Cox Report and their proposals concerning
the 10th anniversary of Tian'anmen incident.
</P>
<P>
Zabala said Argentina and China share similar views on issues
such as independent foreign policies. He expressed hope that the
two countries will further promote military cooperation and
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret for the U.S.-led NATO attack on Chinese
embassy in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed admiration for China's achievements in
economic reform and defense construction.
</P>
<P>
Vice Admiral Shi Yunsheng, commander of the Navy of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army, attended the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
