<HEADLINE> Missing Israeli Navy Submarine Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli navy submarine, which
disappeared with its 69-member crew over 30 years ago, has been
located by two Cypriot vessels working for the Israeli navy, the
Cyprus News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The submarine Dakar was found 3,000 meters deep under the water
in an area between Greece's Crete island, Cyprus and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"We went out there, and we found it," said captain Duncan
Mckenzy of the ship "Flying Enterprise."
</P>
<P>
The search covered a water area 2,500-3,000 meters deep and it
was marked to facilitate the task, the captain said.
</P>
<P>
"The submarine itself showed up very well on the sonar and the
technicians were delighted about it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The recent search for the Dakar started 25 days ago and now it
is up to the Israeli navy to decide whether to evacuate it or not.
</P>
<P>
Dakar disappeared in January 1968 on a journey from England to
the Israeli northern port city of Haifa, where the then Israeli
Prime Minister Golda Meyer was preparing to welcome the vessel to
the country.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the search for Dakar has continued but yielded no
results until last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
