<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Enjoys Rebounding Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The declining influx of overseas
investment in north China's Tianjin Municipality bottomed out
during the first four months of the year and indicated the growing
investment confidence of overseas companies in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Municipal Foreign Trade and Economic
Commission showed that 180 overseas-funded enterprises were
approved during the period, with some 42 related ventures
reporting new investments. Total contracted investments hit 1.04
billion U.S. dollars, with actual overseas investment reaching 565
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Multinational companies continued to be enthusiastic investors,
with projects by five companies alone involving a combined
contracted investment of 114 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Investments from European and American countries continued to
rise. Investment by American businesses rose by 12.2 percent in
the first four months on the annual basis and that by German,
French, British and Japanese businesses went up by 100 to 200
percent in the period. Investments from Southeast Asia are also
rebounding as countries in the region are gradually overcoming the
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Existing overseas-funded enterprises have pledged to increase
investments, with investments for the first four months of the
year hitting 4.06 million U.S. dollars, up 90 percent on the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, real estate development and infrastructure
projects have emerged as the focal points for overseas investment,
along with continuing investment in the new and high technology
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, one of the Chinese cities with the largest volume of
overseas investment, has approved a total of 12,593 overseas-
funded projects involving contracted investments of 24.16 billion
U.S. dollars. The city has thus far used overseas direct
investments totaling 11.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Overseas-funded enterprises have emerged as a pillar of
Tianjin's economy, and the municipal government will continue to
work hard to improve the investment climate to ensure the
profitability of more overseas-funded enterprises," according to
Vice Mayor Li Shenglin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
