<HEADLINE> India Agrees to Visit by Pakistan Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- India has accepted Pakistan's
offer to send its foreign minister Sartaj Aziz to New Delhi to
defuse what caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee
described as a war-like situation in the disputed Jammu and
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman for the External Affairs Ministry said
Monday that the date for Aziz's visit had not been decided and
would be worked out through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister (Vajpayee) has considered and accepted the
offer of Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to send Foreign
Minister Sartaj Aziz to India," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
But he said the Indian armed forces would continue their
operation until they achieve their objective of putting an end to
what India described as armed intrusion in the entire Kargil
sector and restoring the status quo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vajpayee accused Pakistan Monday of trying to alter
the line of control in Jammu and Kashmir and asked Islamabad to
call back the infiltrators even as he accepted Pakistan's offer.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering of traders at his residence here,
Vajpayee said, "This is a kind of aggression," adding that "it is
an attempt to alter the frontiers and a move to grab part of our
land."
</P>
<P>
Defense Ministry sources said Monday that the Indian Air Force
continued its air strikes in Kargil sector of Kashmir for the
sixth day Monday.
</P>
<P>
India claimed to have killed some 400 intruders backed by
Pakistan in the past few days while Indian casualties stood at 33
killed, 130 wounded and 12 missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
