<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares closed trading
slightly firmer Monday as solid gains on Wall Street outweighed
the effect of a record trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index gained 11.6 points in what
dealers described as lackluster trade to close at 2900.2, after
hitting a high of 2904.2 during the day.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was responsible for most of the
gains, picking up 31.4 points to 5145.8, while the all resources
index fell 8.6 points to 1089.6.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics on Monday morning announced
the trade balance on Australia's goods and services was a deficit
of 1.23 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover on the market was 272.12 million shares
traded for 402.05 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Falls outweighed rises 599 to 559 while there were 438 steady.
</P>
<P>
Much of the market's strength was coming from the banking
sector which rose 139.4 points to 6709.9.
</P>
<P>
Market leader National Australia Bank was 64.7 cents stronger
at 25.459 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Westpac bank were 19.6 cents higher at 10.686
Australian dollars. The Commonwealth Bank of Australia gained 52
cents to 25.15 Australian dollars and ANZ bank was 19.9 cents up
at 11.32 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, diversified miner BHP lost 25.1 cents
to 15.477 Australian dollars while global miner Rio Tinto dropped
20 cents to 21.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold sector, which has suffered a battering recently, made
ground Monday, rising 12.1 points to 863.1 points.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold bullion closed in Sydney at 270.10 U.S.
dollars, down from 271.25 U.S. dollars on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
