<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower on Record Trade Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed lower
Monday after the announcement of a record monthly trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the Australian dollar fell when the trade figures
were announced, but edged back in afternoon trade to close at
64.97 U.S. cents from 65.24 U.S. cents on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Australia's goods and services trade deficit blew out to a
record 1.9 billion Australian dollars (1.23 billion U.S. dollars)
in April as exports plunged to a two-year low, the Australian
Bureau of Statistics said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although peaking at 65.33 U.S. cents early Monday morning, the
Australian dollar spent most of the day trading between 64.79 and
64.99 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also closed at 0.6211 euro from 0.6264
euro at the close on Friday and 78.85 Japanese yen from 78.70 yen.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
