<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Bank of Israel will keep the interest rate
unchanged at 12 percent in June, a spokesman for the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
This decision was taken in order to continue policies to
achieve an annual inflation rate of 4 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that budget steps must be taken as soon
as possible to keep the budget deficit within 2 percent of the
Gross Domestic Product in 1999 as required by Israeli laws.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's gasoline imports rose sharply in the
first four months of 1999 compared to the same period last year,
according to a report released by the National Infrastructure
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The biggest increase was recorded in the civilian sector, which
had a 340 percent increase, or 109,530 tons.
</P>
<P>
Energy experts said the sharp increase was directly attributed
to the purchase of the energy company Granit Hacarmel by the
international trading company Glencore last fall.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's imports of almost all durable consuming
products, including cars, refrigerators, videos, furniture,
washing machines and dishwashers, declined in April, compared with
last month this year or the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the declines were attributed to the slow pace of new
housing sales in April.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Industrial investments in the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states increased by 180 per cent over the past 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Monday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" quoted the Secretary General of
the Gulf Industrial Investment Organisation Abdul Rahman Al
Jaafari as sayig that investments have increased from 28 billion
U.S. dollars in 1988 to over 80 billion dollars in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
