<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Employees to Hold Shares, Key Positions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Employees of the Philippine Airlines
(PAL) are now part-owners of the flag carrier as PAL chairman
Lucio Tan has raised the needed 200 million U.S. dollars for its
rehabilitation, Philippine President Joseph Estrada said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the PAL employees were given 60,000 shares in the
airline, along with a seat in the board of directors and one seat
in the PAL advisors committee.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that this will rehabilitate PAL," he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said Tan and his investor-partners assured him Sunday
that they have raised the 200 million U.S. dollars needed to keep
the PAL in business.
</P>
<P>
He said that once Tan and his group complete the infusion of
the required capital into the airline, there would be no need to
scout for other foreign investors to save the PAL.
</P>
<P>
However, other investors can come in once the 200 million U.S.
dollars turns out to be insufficient to rehabilitate the airline,
he added.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, stockholders of the PAL ratified a resolution of the
airline's board of directors that formally approved the airline's
amended rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
The stockholders also ratified a board resolution which reduced
the par value of existing shares from five pesos (0.13 U.S. cent)
to one peso (0.02 U.S. cent) per share and increased the number of
shares from 4 billion to 20 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
