<HEADLINE> Cambodia Seeks Peaceful Way to Solve Border Issues: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia will seek peaceful way
to solve the border and immigration issues with Vietnam, Cambodian
National Assembly President Prince Norodom Ranariddh said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh returned home Monday after ending a week-long
official visit to Vietnam at the invitation of Vietnamese National
Assembly Chairman Nong Duc Manh.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh told the reporters at the Pochentong airport that all
the leaders of Vietnam expressed their eagerness to resolve the
border and immigration issues between the two countries before the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
The aim, he said, was to allow the two countries "to
concentrate our energy on building new friendship and cooperative
relations in various fields, especially in the fields of economy
and trade."
</P>
<P>
He said, "as to the issue of the Vietnamese residents in
Cambodia, the king and I also insisted that it is resolved in a
peaceful way and in accordance with the law."
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Ranariddh met with his Vietnamese counterpart
National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc Manh, President Tran Duc
Luong, Prime Minister Phan Van Khai and Communist Party General
Secretary Le Kha Phieu.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a memorandum on cooperation between the
parliaments of the two countries. They also agreed to solve the
long-standing border disputes by the year 2000 and boost trade
ties. Meanwhile, Hanoi also expressed the hope that Cambodia will
ease tense living conditions for Vietnamese residents in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
It was announced here that Vietnamese Communist Party General
Secretary Le Kha Phieu will pay a state visit to Cambodia next
week at the invitation of King Norodom Sihanouk and Queen
Monineath.
</P>
<P>
Phieu is also expected to discuss the sensitive border and
immigration issues.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Prince Ranariddh leads the National
Assembly delegation to pay an official visit abroad since he
became President of National Assembly last November. The prince
last visited Vietnam in 1995 when he was co-prime minister of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The visit also comes less than one month after Cambodia
formally became the member of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations at a special ceremony held in Hanoi on April 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
