<HEADLINE> Cigarette Ads Banned in No Smoking Day in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PEHN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Cigarette advertisements were
banned here Monday by the Cambodian government to observe the
World No Smoking Day.
</P>
<P>
No tobacco commercial advertisements would be seen or heard
today, the Ministry of Information said, adding it was just a
trial which will eventually lead to a nationwide ban on tobacco
advertising in print and broadcast media.
</P>
<P>
The World No Smoking Day, which falls on May 31 and was
sponsored by the World Health Organization, aimed to draw
attention to the serious impact of tobacco on health.
</P>
<P>
A survey found that cigarette advertisements have increased 400
percent from 1993 to 1997 in Cambodia, the Cambodia Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 86 percent of male population in the
rural areas smoke regularly and about 62 percent in urban areas.
Female smokers account for only five percent of the women
population in the country.
</P>
<P>
An apparent increase in the country's smoking population and
its potential to increase instances of lung cancer and heart
attack have already caused the concern of the Health Ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
