<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Mark 70th Anniversary of Peking Man Discovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences (
CAS), China's top scientific research body, plans to sponsor an
international symposium between October 12-16 to celebrate the 70
th anniversary of the discovery of Peking Man fossils.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the paleoanthropological symposium will discuss
topics related to the origin of human beings and the living
conditions of ancient humans, according to Dr. Dong Junshe of the
Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology under
the CAS.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists discovered the remnants of remote ape-like
humans in Yuanmou, Yunnan Province, as well as Wushan in Sichuan
Province and Fanchang in Anhui Province in recent years, according
to Dong.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts place great importance to the date 70 years ago
when Pei Wenzhong, a leading Chinese archeologist at the time,
discovered the first broken skull of Peking Man who lived some 500,
000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Jia Lanpo, a senior CAS academician, stunned the world in 1936
with the discovery of three fossilized skulls of Peking Man and
other cultural treasures near Zhoukoudian in the southwestern
suburbs of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) listed the Zhoukoudian site as a World
Heritage in 1987.
</P>
<P>
However, the six invaluable intact skullcaps disappeared
without a trace during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen prominent Chinese scientist published a global appeal
last year seeking assistance in locating parts of the skulls of
Peking Man.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Urges Further SOE Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China is currently faced with the
major task of rejuvenating state-owned enterprises (SOEs) under
the conditions of the socialist market economy, according to
President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party
and chairman of the Central Military Commission, made the comment
during a fact-finding tour of central China's Hubei Province
between May 25-30.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the pioneering effort to develop a market economy
while upholding the socialist system, and noted the lack of ready-
made solutions.
</P>
<P>
"We must emancipate our minds, seek truth from facts and
continue to carry out bold explorations favorable to promoting the
growth of productive forces of socialist society, increasing the
overall strength of socialist state and raising the living
standards of Chinese citizens," Jiang told local officials.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that Chinese people are fully capable
of overcoming any difficulty and obstacles encountered as long as
the Communist Party of China and society as a whole remain closely
united.
</P>
<P>
Jiang has completed three special fact-finding tours this year
to investigate and study issues related to the reform and
development of SOEs.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's current trip featured visits to the Aeolux Automotive
Industrial Corp. in Shiyan, a textile mill in Xiangfan and a steel
plant in the Hubei provincial capital of Wuhan.
</P>
