<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PAL Stockholders Approve Rehabilitation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Stockholders of Philippine Airlines
(PAL) ratified here Monday a resolution of the airline's board of
directors that formally approved the national flag carrier's
amended rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
At a special meeting presided over by PAL Chairman Lucio Tan,
the stockholders ratified the board's decision on May 14 to accept
the plan as submitted, as well as any adjustments that may arise
from the company's acceptance of the terms and conditions of the
investment from prospective investors.
</P>
<P>
The stockholders also ratified a board resolution which reduced
the par value of existing shares from five pesos (0.13 U.S. cent)
to one peso (0.02 U.S. cent) per share and increased the number of
shares from 4 billion to 20 billion.
</P>
<P>
Such revaluation is deemed imperative in order to attract
investors to infuse the required 200 million U.S. dollars in new
equity, as called for in the rehabilitation plan, PAL said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Since its submission to the Stock Exchange Commission (SEC) on
March 15, the amended rehabilitation plan, which incorporated key
changes to the original plan, has been conditionally accepted by
the majority of PAL's creditors.
</P>
<P>
Based on the majority support, the SEC approved the plan on May
17 subject to the equity infusion of 200 million dollars not later
than June 4.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, President Joseph Estrada said that his
government will save PAL, whose debts has amounted to 2.2 billion
dollars, and keep it flying at all costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
