<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Begin to Arrive at Turkish Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes have begun to arrive
at a military base in western Turkey in a bid to expand air
attacks against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, C-5 and C-17 cargo planes belonging to the U.S. Air
Forces carried logistic materials and NATO soldiers to the
Balikesir air base in western Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a Turkish source, who asked not to be named,
as saying that F-16 and F-15 fighter jets of the U.S. Air Forces
have begun to arrive at the Balikesir base.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 36 fighter jets will be deployed at the
air base in Balikesir and other 18 warplanes will be deployed at
the air base in Bandirma.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Treaty Organization decided to deploy 72
fighter jets, including 18 Turkish warplanes at three Turkish
military bases for its air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The United States-led western military bloc is expected to
launch attacks on the targets in Yugoslavia from Turkey via an
air corridor over Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4,000 U.S. personnel will soon arrive at the
military bases in Balikesir and Bandirma in western Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
