<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cities Face Uphill Battle Against Air Pollution (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Members of the National People's
Congress, China's highest legislative body, said today that major
cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and Xi'an continue to face
grim air pollution in spite of the recent improvement in the
general situation.
</P>
<P>
The legislators made the comment during a meeting culminating
fact-finding tours to five cities, including Lanzhou in the
northwest and Shenyang in northeast. They also discussed
implementation of the law on preventing air pollution.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing continues to rank as the most contaminated capital
city in the world and one of the worst in China in terms of air
quality," said Qu Geping, chairman of the NPC Environment and
Resources Committee who participated in the tour of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The latest air pollution index for May 7-13 showed that
Beijing's index was 40 percent higher than Shanghai, 33 percent
greater than Tianjin and 37 percent above Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
The most prevalent pollutants in Beijing resulted from burning
of coal, auto emissions, dust storms and heavy industries, said Qu,
noting that coal consumption accounted for 70 percent of energy
used in the capital, with motor vehicles contributing some 63
percent of carbon monoxide and 50 percent of nitrogen oxide.
</P>
<P>
Central authorities have paid great attention to the situation
in recent months, with Beijing responding by adopting 46 emergency
measures to tackle the problem, including banning the use of coal
in certain areas, removing substandard cabs from the road and
planting more trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cities Face Uphill Battle Against Air Pollution (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ratios for sulfur dioxide and carbon monoxide in the air
are decreasing when compared to last year and the rising level of
nitrogen oxide has been curbed. However, the volume of floating
particles continues to climb.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the nation's largest economic and financial city,
has sharply reduced its pollution index in recent years by
introducing environment-friendly cars and planting more trees.
Nonetheless, acid rain has emerged as an increasing problem in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang, one of China's largest bases for heavy industry, has
also witnessed some improvement in air quality in spite of
increased coal consumption and ongoing economic development.
</P>
<P>
Zou Jiahua, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee,
stressed that "Chinese cities will continue to face an uphill
battle against air pollution and much more needs to be done to
meet the demands of the general public."
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers tables a number of proposals during the meeting,
including the designation of high population density areas in
Beijing as "coal free zones" and expanding the production of
automobiles using gas as the fuel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
