<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Output of Timber Undergoes Sharp Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China's output of timber in the
first quarter this year plummeted 20.7 percent on an annual basis,
according to the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures show that the output of timber from January to
March totaled 9.9 million cubic meters with an output of 3.1
million cubic meters in March.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has imposed ban on irrational lumbering
in many forest areas, particularly those on the upper reaches of
major rivers in a bid to curb soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Many experts have blamed the excessive logging of trees in the
past as one of the major reasons for last summer's devastating
flooding in southern and northeastern China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Steel Production on Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China witnessed growing steel
production in the first quarter this year with the output growing
8.1 percent year on year to 29.2 million tons, according to the
National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The output of rolled steel during the period amounted to 27.2
million tons, surging 15.1 percent on an annual basis, the bureau
said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, production of pig iron grew by 7.6 percent
over the same months last year to 29.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The period also saw a year-on-year increase of 12.9 percent in
the output of non-ferrous metals. In the first three months, the
country turned out 1.5 million tons of non-ferrous metals.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the output of aluminium oxide hit 898,000
tons, up 14.6 percent on an annual basis, and that of aluminium
products hit 318,800 tons, surging 23.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the production of copper products increased
by 20.7 percent over the same period last year to 260,000 tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Output of Major Chemicals Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China's chemical industry has
maintained its growing momentum with the output of most major
products keeping on the rise in the first quarter this year,
according to the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The production of chemical fertilizers from January to March
increased by 14 percent on an annual basis to 7.6 million tons,
and that of chemical pesticides surged 13.7 percent to 154,500
tons.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 1.34 million tons of chemical fiber were
produced, surging 15.1 percent, while 1.88 million tons of plastic
products were turned out, up 12.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The output of ethylene grew 17.4 percent year-on-year to 1.1
million tons and that of plastic resin rose 14.5 percent to 1.9
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Production of caustic soda edged up 1.4 percent to 1.3 million
tons, and that of sulphuric acid surged 15.2 percent to 5.25
million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
