<HEADLINE> HK Scholar Conferred Honorary Title of Yale University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Professor Charles K. Kao,
president of the Hong Kong Academy of Engineering Sciences, has
been conferred an honorary degree of Doctor of Science by Yale
University, the academy said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The honorary title was conferred in recognition of Kao's
achievements as an inventor and an educator, according to the
citation, which said Kao's pioneering research "changed the way
the world communicates."
</P>
<P>
Kao's invention has been used to create worldwide networks of
voice and data transmission.
</P>
<P>
After retirement from the vice-chancellorship of the Chinese
University of Hong Kong in 1996, Kao established his own
technology transfer consultancy company. One of his current
projects is to help transform Hong Kong into a world class
information city. 
</P>
