<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Province Set to Improve Ecology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
will focus on 10 major ecological projects between now and 2003 in
an effort to effectively improve the ecology within a relatively
short period of time.
</P>
<P>
The wide-ranging projects will center on harnessing slopes and
small valleys, water conservancy, afforestation, protecting
natural forests and grasslands, and promoting ecological
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 percent of Hunan's one million ha of farmland with
slopes of less than 25 degrees will be transformed into high
standard terraced fields by the year 2003 and will thereby reduce
erosion by 47 million tons annually, according to one provincial
official.
</P>
<P>
He added that a substantial portion of farmland with slopes of
more than 25 degrees will be transformed into ecologically-sound
forests.
</P>
<P>
Trees will be planted on hills covering 2.57 million ha and
grass will be planted on 200,000 ha in the upper and middle
reaches of major rivers by 2003, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He said that water conservancy projects will help reclaim
cropland covering 3,300 ha by the year 2003.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
