<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 08:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan Resume Summit Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
resumed talks with Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein Monday
morning amid intensified efforts to forge a unified Arab stance
on negotiations with a new Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
The talks dealt with the latest developments in the Middle East
peace process following the Israeli elections and means of
boosting bilateral relations, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Hopes to revive the peace process increased after Ehud Barak,
leader of Israel's Labor Party, defeated hardline Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
Barak has pledged to push the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks
forward and reactivate the negotiations with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan have been consulting with the three Arab
parties directly related to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah hosted Lebanese President Emile Lahoud on Saturday,
two days after he visited Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in the
Gaza Strip. Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa met with Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad on Saturday in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian king arrived in Cairo Sunday evening for a
two-day visit and discussed with Mubarak the prospects for a
five-way summit to be attended by leaders of Egypt, Jordan, Syria,
Lebanon and the Palestinians, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
But Moussa said Sunday after the talks that an Arab five-way
summit will not be held before Barak forms his government and
announces its programs.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called for the five-way summit after a meeting in Cairo
with Mubarak on May 23, out of concern that Israel would try to
divide Arab ranks by cutting separate peace deals with Syria and
Lebanon without finding a settlement to the Palestinian issue -
the core of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
But so far, Syria has shown little interest in Arafat's
proposal. Damascus is still keeping distance with the Palestinians
due to the Palestinians' signing of interim peace accords
separately with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moussa disclosed that the presidents of Egypt and Syria will
meet in the Egyptian capital in June, an apparent effort to
persuade al-Assad to attend the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
