<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Grain Prices Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China's April grain purchase prices
for state-owned grain enterprises fell one percent on March, with
prices on grain wholesale markets sliding marginally.
</P>
<P>
The average April purchase price for wheat, maize, and rice was
set at 60.4 yuan per 50 kilograms, a level essentially the same as
in March. However, the sales price fell 70 yuan, down 0.7 yuan or
1 percent on the previous month, according to the State
Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Despite the marginal drop, market prices for various varieties
of grain were seven to 15 yuan higher than purchase prices, a
range which essentially enabled grain businesses to cover costs.
</P>
<P>
Prices for polished long-grained nonglutinous rice and polished
round-grained nonglutinous rice rose by between 5-15 percentage
points compared with last year's same period, while prices for
maize and soybeans fell 9.2 percent and 23.1 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China harvested more than 490 billion kg of grain last year and
managed to maintain balanced supply and demand, with some areas
reporting an oversupply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
