<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Producers Fail to Learn From Past Lessons, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A major economist of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) has said that Arab oil producing countries
failed to learn from past lessons in dealing with the latest drop
in oil prices, the Gulf News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Oil producing countries had gone through many crises like the
latest one of the drop of oil prices. However, they dealt with
these in an ad hoc manner and did not make use of the lessons of
the past," Dr. Fatimah Al Shamsi, vice-dean of Economics and
Administration Faculty at the UAE National University has said.
</P>
<P>
"None of these countries had specific strategies and policies
to react toward such crises which had been taking place all
along," she said while addressing a symposium on the effects of
the drop in oil prices on the economies of Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
In December 1985, the oil price was 27.5 U.S. dollars per
barrel, but it dropped to 8.5 dollars in December 1998, the
economist added.
</P>
<P>
She urged oil producing and exporting countries to take
initiatives in dealing with oil prices, saying these countries
have to be more active in coordination.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices should be fixed by producing and exporting
countries, instead of being controlled and determined by importing
countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
With the oil demand declining in South Asia and other markets,
it has become compulsory for oil producing countries to reduce
their production through a clear understanding between themselves,
she noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
