<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Discover Earliest Imperial Garden in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
recently discovered a 3,600-year-old imperial garden in central
China's Henan Province, which is believed to be the origin of all
Chinese gardens, including Beijing's Summer Palace.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said this is the earliest imperial garden they
have ever found in China. In the center of the garden is a 130
meter by 20 meter pond connecting with a dyke and a moat, from
which archeologists have discovered fishing tackle made of jade
and pottery, and a number of shells.
</P>
<P>
The garden is in Yanshi city, some 700 kilometers from Beijing,
where archeologists discovered in the 1980s the capital site of
the Shang Dynasty (16 to 11 B.C.). The garden is still being
excavated in the ancient palace area of the city.
</P>
<P>
Near the pond was an ancient well, from which the archeologists
unearthed a special pot. They are hopeful that the ruins of
pavilions and other potential sight-seeing buildings will also be
found.
</P>
<P>
"The pond is the oldest and the most complete water facility in
China, which was used during carnivals for the emperors. It also
improved the ecology," said Du Jinpeng, an archeologists from the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Almost every Chinese emperor built big gardens in their palace
areas, featuring man-made rivers, ponds, rockeries and plantings.
The most famous was the Yuanming Yuan (the Round Bright Garden) a
few miles to the northwest of Beijing, which was destroyed by
British and French troops in 1860.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists hold that the discovery will benefit the
study of the evolution of Chinese cities and of the history of
Chinese gardens and water facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Strengthens Control on Infrastructure Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Agricultural Bank of China (ABC)
today issued a circular about strengthening the management of
loans for infrastructure and fixed asset construction projects.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ABC said that the circular aims to step up
related credit management, minimize credit risks and promote the
healthy development of credit businesses.
</P>
<P>
In the circular, the ABC clearly spells out the key areas of
infrastructure and fixed assets that are appropriate for using
such loans, and demands that all of its branches stop lending to
repetitive projects and strictly control loans to manufacturing
projects.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure loans should support projects that can yield
good profits and are capable of repaying the principal and
interests, including rural power networks, energy and
communications, telecommunications and urban water and energy
supply, as well as medical infrastructure construction projects.
</P>
<P>
Fixed asset loans are earmarked for supporting new and high-
tech enterprises, as well as real estate and residential housing
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The circular also standardizes credit appraisal procedures and
relevant rights and responsibilities, and stipulates the need for
risk control of the bank's loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
