<HEADLINE> U.N. Peacekeeper Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A member of the United Nations
peacekeeping forces in south Lebanon was killed and another one
wounded in conflicts between Lebanese guerrillas and Israeli
forces Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Orient radio quoted security sources as saying both
peacekeepers were from the Irish contingent of the U.N. Interim
Forces in Lebanon (UNIFIL).
</P>
<P>
The fatality occurred during the armed conflicts between
guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and
Israeli forces in the western sector of its occupied border zone
in south Lebanon, the source said, adding a Lebanese woman was
also wounded in the clash.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli forces and its ally
South Lebanon Army out of the country.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong U.N. forces were deployed in the border zone in
1978 following the Israeli first invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The forces, charged with overseeing the withdrawal of Israeli
troops, were made up of soldiers from Ireland, Ghana, Nepal, Fiji,
Norway, Finland, Poland, France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 of the UNIFIL have been killed in various incidents,
especially during conflicts between Lebanese guerillas and Israeli
forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
