<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Domestic Sources to Fund Half of Dhaka's Annual Development Programs: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Around 50 percent of the budget for
Bangladesh's annual development programs (ADPs) of the coming
1999-2000 fiscal year will be funded from internal sources, a
report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed size of the annual development budget would be 155
billion taka (3.23 billion U.S. dollars), and the local
mobilization of fund for the ADPs would amount to 78.03 billion
taka (1.63 billion dollars), or 50.3 percent of the total, The New
Nation daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The percentage shows a sharp rise from that of the current
1998-99 fiscal year ending on June 30. The revised ADPs in the
current fiscal year got only 41.5 percent funding from internal
sources, according to the latest available estimation.
</P>
<P>
The revised ADPs budget this year would be slashed to 140
billion taka (2.92 billion dollars) from its original size of 150
billion taka (3.13 billion dollars), sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, government policy makers earlier had
a plan to make the size of the revenue budget at about 176 billion
taka (3.67 billion dollars) for the coming fiscal, but later
decided to slim the size in order to divert more fund from the
revenue budget to the development budget, so that the major
portion of fund for the implementation of development programs
could be met from internal sources and without increasing extra
tax loads on the people, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the government was also planning to
procure funds from Bangladeshi expatriates abroad for meeting part
of the development budget, in order to reduce dependence on donor
funding.
</P>
<P>
The funding of ADPs from internal sources would depend largely
on the skill and efficiency in mobilizing local resources and
fiscal measure, and the government was likely to give more
importance to the process of revenue collection and resource
mobilization than to raising tax rates, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh may not be able to complete all the development
activities under the country's ADP for the current fiscal year, as
only 44 percent of the ADP development activities were completed
during the first eight months, as against the target of 66.66
percent, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Planning Ministry said that only about 43
percent of the total fund allocated for the ADP had been spent in
the eight-month period, and it was a great challenge to spend the
rest 57 percent to successfully implement the activities in the
remaining months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
