<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Targets 300 Million Tons of Onshore Oil and Gas By 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China is set to develop six oil and
gas fields at home and abroad with a production capacity of 50
million tons each by 2010 in a bid to meet the joint target of
producing 300 million tons of onshore oil and gas by that time.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the China National Petroleum Corp. (
CNPC), the six large oil and gas fields include four domestic ones
and two in foreign countries which will be cooperative projects
with foreign oil companies.
</P>
<P>
The domestic fields are located in four major areas including
the Songliao Basin in northeast China, the Bohai Bay Basin and the
western part of China, as well as gas fields in Sichuan, Shaanxi-
Gansu-Ningxia areas and Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region whose
combined gas production capacity will reach 50 billion cubic
meters (equivalent to 50 million tons of oil).
</P>
<P>
From overseas oil and gas fields China will on the one hand
import 50 million tons of oil and on the other some 50 billion
cubic meters of natural gas from neighboring countries (equivalent
to 50 million tons of oil).
</P>
<P>
Thus by 2010, CNPC will be able to bring to the market a total
of 200 million tons of crude oil and 100 billion cubic meters of
natural gas (equivalent to 100 million tons of oil). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9 Garment Factories Begin Operation in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Nine garment factories built at a
cost of 260 million rupees (3.7 million U.S. dollars) in southern
Sri Lanka have already commenced operations employing over 3,000
youths, the official Daily News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Ministry of Industrial Development told the
paper that the factories were built under a 25-garment factory
program.
</P>
<P>
The nine factories are located at Batapola, Karandeniya,
Malimbada, Udukawa, Deniyaya, Niyagama, Devinuwara, Matara and
Galle.
</P>
<P>
Four other factories are due to commence operations within the
next two months employing 1,800 youths, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that once the 25-factory program is completed in the
south, 8,000 youths will be provided direct employment and 16,500
with indirect employment.
</P>
<P>
The government has offered an eight-year tax holiday to
investors who set up factories in very difficult areas and a
five-year tax holiday for those investing in difficult areas.
</P>
<P>
Investors can import machinery and other equipment duty free.
They are also entitled to duty free vehicles depending on the
workforce employed.
</P>
<P>
Under quota allocation, 25,000 dozens of garments have been
allocated to factories in very difficult areas, 12,000 dozens to
factories in difficult areas and 6,000 dozens for other factories
which employ over 250 persons.
</P>
<P>
The quota allocation will be doubled for factories which employ
more than 500 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parties Slam Government Policy on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Several political parties in Germany
on Monday strongly criticized NATO and the German government for
their Kosovo policies.
</P>
<P>
Angelika Beer, a member of the Green Party, one of the ruling
parties in Germany, in a speech published in Monday's Focus
magazine, slashed out at "NATO's ridiculous strategy" on the
Kosovo issue and described it as "a total failure."
</P>
<P>
NATO has been bombing Yugoslavia wantonly in a bid to press
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept its demands of
complete withdrawal of Yugoslav military forces and deployment of
a NATO-led international forces in Kosovo, a Yugoslav province
mostly populated by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Beer, an official in charge of defense policies, slammed Vice-
Chancellor and Minister of Foreign Affairs Joschka Fischer (a
Green Party member) as too obedient with the United States, asking
him to explain to the Green Party parliamentary group where the
Kosovo conflict is leading to.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking through the radio of the Heessen state, she urged
the German parliament to reevaluate the current situation in
Kosovo. As a member of NATO, Germany has taken part in the
alliance's air operations in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Gunda Roestel, a member of the Green Party Presidium, in a
speech carried on the same day in the Der Spiegel magazine,
expressed strong opposition to any deployment of ground troops in
Kosovo without a mandate of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to more and more signs that NATO would soon send
ground forces to the troubled Yugoslav province, Roestel dismissed
it as "extremely ridiculous to believe that ground operations
would bring a quick end to the Kosovo conflict. (If ground troops
are resorted to,) such craziness would last for months, if not
years."
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Wolfgang Schaeuble, chairman of the Christian
Democratic Union (CDU), the biggest opposition party, criticized
the German government for making a serious mistake on the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Another major political party, the Free Democratic Party,
echoed the Greens and CDU at the end of its congress in Bremen on
Monday by calling for an immediate end to NATO's bombing of
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
