<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Green Sweeps Sprint Double in Track Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- World 100-meter champion Maurice
Greene of the United States swept the sprint double Sunday in the
Prefontaine Classic Athletics Meet in Eugene, Oregon of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
World women's fastest sprinter Marion Jones and American
Olympic 400-meter champion Michael Johnson also won their
specialties.
</P>
<P>
Greene won the 100 meters in 9.84 seconds, a time that equaled
Canadian Donovan Bailey's world record but was negated by a wind
of 7.83 mph, well over the allowable of 4.473 for record standard.
</P>
<P>
Forty minutes later, Greene won the 200 in 20.06, a time that
would have broken the meet record of 20.15 by Johnson in 1995, if
not for the wind.
</P>
<P>
Green will face Johnson in a 200 showdown at the USA
Championships next month, the qualifying meet for the World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
Jones, track and field's woman athlete of the year in the past
two years, won the 200 in the fastest time in the world this year
at 21.81.
</P>
<P>
"I want to go through the season undefeated because I've yet to
do that," said Jones, who lost only once last year in her final
competition with the long jump.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, ranked No.1 in the world in the 400 eight times, beat
world No. 2 Mark Richardson of Britain by about 10 meters at 44.51.
</P>
<P>
"The wind was blowing hard down the backstretch, so running a
good time today was pretty much impossible," said Johnson, who
thought he was in shape to break 44 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Larry Wade of the United States ran a year's fastest time of 13.
12 in the men's 110 meters hurdles, his countryman Reggie Torian
finished 13.17 in second. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Helps Tibet Monitor Grasslands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Local experts are working on a
project to issue forecasts on the growth of grass for herdsmen in
the northern part of the Tibet Autonomous Region according to U.S.
meteorological satellite data.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time that Tibet uses the satellite-based
remote sensing technology for husbandry, says Yang Zhigang, head
of the Remote Sensing Application Research Center under the
regional meteorological bureau.
</P>
<P>
The center, which is responsible for the project, has set up
three monitoring stations in northern Tibet and the stations will
send accurate data on the height and coverage of grass to the
bureau in Lhasa, the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
The northern Tibet husbandry area, the largest of its kind in
the country, is so vulnerable to natural calamities like drought,
snowstorm, windstorm and low temperature that its output of grass
and livestock are much lower than grasslands in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities hope to renovate the grass production,
control the amount of animals and upgrade the husbandry industry
with the satellite-based remote sensing technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
