<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Receives WHO Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has received the Tobacco Free World Award from the
World Health Organization (WHO), the Presidential Secretariat
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
WHO Director General Dr. Gro Harlem Bruntland has cited
President Kumaratunga as the recipient of this award for her
outstanding contribution towards addressing health and economic
problems connected to the consumption of tobacco, the secretariat
said.
</P>
<P>
WHO annually sponsors the World No Tobacco Day which falls on
May 31 to draw attention to the serious impact of tobacco on
health.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government, on an unprecedented initiative taken
by President Kumaratunga, has developed a National Policy on
Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The goal of this policy is to improve the health and well-being
of all Sri Lankans, increase productivity and alleviate poverty by
achieving a sustained reduction and the eventual elimination of
all tobacco use and tobacco-related harm.
</P>
<P>
Specific objectives of the policy are to prevent commencement
of tobacco use by non-users, to encourage current users to stop
using tobacco, to minimize voluntary exposure to non-users to
tobacco use, to uphold the right of non-smokers and to create an
environment free of contamination from tobacco smoke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
