<HEADLINE> Highlights of Weekly Trade News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major trade news in
China between May 24 and 30:
</P>
<P>
-- A total of 3,271 overseas-funded enterprises were
registered in the first quarter of this year, down 16.9 percent
from the same period last year, according to the State
Administration for Industry and Commerce (SAIC).
</P>
<P>
-- The '99 Beijing International Hi-Tech Industry Week (May 20-
24) closed here last Monday after concluding 27 contracts
involving a total investment of 680 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese officials and business people are calling for
increased investment in Central Asia in an effort to boost its
trade with the region. The government will formulate policies to
encourage investment in agriculture, energy, technology, equipment,
and labor in central Asia.
</P>
<P>
-- China continues to be firm in its opening-up policy in the
economic and technological development zones and hopes to increase
their use of overseas investment, Shi Guangsheng, minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), said at a
conference on overseas investment in state-level economic and
technological development zones which started in Shanghai last
Monday.
</P>
<P>
--- China and Kyrgyzstan agreed last Tuesday to increase
economic and trade relations during a meeting of Zhang Xiang, a
vice-minister of MOFTEC, and Muratbek Sansyzbayevich Yimanaliyev,
the Kyrgyzstan foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
-- China's first Sino-American trading company began operation
last Tuesday in Shenzhen, the country's first special economic
zone. With capital of 12 million U.S. dollars, the Shenzhen Sino-
American OCT International Trading Company Ltd. has been approved
by MOFTEC to engage in import and export business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Weekly Trade News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- China's imports from Russia surged a record 42 percent in
the first four months of the year, hitting 1.374 billion U.S.
dollars, according to latest statistics from the General
Administration of Customs. Total bilateral trade volume between
China and Russia grew 1.7 percent in the period, reaching 1.710
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- China has never changed its position, viewpoint and attitude
on accession into the World Trade Organization (WTO), Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here last Thursday at
a regular press conference. China has a consistent position on WTO
negotiations, he reiterated, and what China insists on is "the
balance between rights and obligations".
</P>
<P>
-- China will open wider to the outside world and make better
utilization of overseas investments with the advent of a new
century, said Wu Yi, alternate member of the Political Bureau of
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and a
state councilor, last Wednesday at a national conference on
foreign investment utilization in national economic and technical
development zones, which was convened in Shanghai between May 24
and 26.
</P>
<P>
-- China's State Council last Friday cut the rate of stamp tax
on B share trading from 0.4 percent to 0.3 percent, in a bid to
boost the B share market reserved for overseas investors. The new
rate will take effect on June 1 and tax revenue will continue to
be shared between the central and the local coffers in the ratio
of 88:12.
</P>
<P>
-- Plans for a big shake up in the way manufacturing and
processing joint ventures are managed in China have been announced
by MOFTEC Shi Guangsheng. Shi outlined details of the plan at a
conference focused on the issue here last Friday and revealed that
a series of new measures to refine the procedures affecting such
ventures will become effective on June 1.
</P>
<P>
-- China's imports of steel between January and April surged 40.
6 percent in tonnage over the same period last year, mainly
because of plunging price of steel products on the international
market. China imported a total of 5.12 million tons of steel in
the first four months, valued at 2.245 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
