<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major Beijing-
based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's state-owned enterprises need dynamic management
systems and operating mechanisms and should keep improving
themselves to deal with challenges facing the socialist market
economy, President Jiang Zemin told a two-day symposium held in
Wuhan City in central China's Hubei Province between May 29-30.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said reforms and development in state-owned enterprises
will play a key role in the country's economic restructuring
efforts and that they deserve the attention of the Party and all
government departments.
</P>
<P>
-- China's ninth five-year scientific development plan (1996 to
2000) has generated fruitful results in the past three years. The
98 major scientific research programs helped increase the total
industrial output value by 31.33 billion yuan (3.7 billion U.S.
dollars) in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), attended yesterday a grand gathering at
Beijing-based Center of Chinese Children for celebrating the
coming International Children's Day on June 1.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of children attended the celebration
activities arranged by the center.
</P>
<P>
-- China's 360 million children witness a healthy growth with
dropping of infants' death rate and increasing of the enrollment
rate of children at school age.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China firmly opposes using the human rights issue to impose
pressure on other countries, and any attempts to use the pretext
of human rights to interfere in China's internal affairs are
doomed to fail, a leading official of the NPC's Foreign Affairs
Committee said in a statement yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Alarmed by the non-stop reduction in the amount of total
arable land, the Ministry of Land and Resources and Ministry of
Agriculture have jointly issued a notice to protect basic farmland.
</P>
<P>
The notice issued last week requires the governments at
different levels, especially those at county and village levels ,
to include the farmland as stipulated by the regulations in their
respective basic arable land protection zones.  
</P>
