<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Forces Repulse Rebel Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav military said it has
repulsed attacks launched by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA)
in the Morina area of southern Kosovo adjacent to Albania, said a
report reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Lazarevici, commander-in-chief of the Yugoslav forces
stationed in Kosovo, was quoted as saying that about 600 KLA men,
armed with NATO-provided heavy weapons, staged attacks on Sunday
along the road connecting Albania's Kukes and Yugoslavia's Prizren,
in an attempt to enter Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Lazarevici pointed out that the attacks demonstrated the NATO
invasion has entered a new stage and described the KLA terrorists
as the advance contingent of NATO, which has been preparing for
ground attacks against Yugoslavia in addition to the incessant
fierce bombings.
</P>
<P>
No information about casualties or other details is available
now.
</P>
<P>
The KLA has been fighting for the independence of Kosovo, a
province of the Serbian Republic of Yugoslavia. The rebel group
has set up bases in northern Albania bordering Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that recently several clashes have occurred
between the KLA and the Yugoslav forces in the Albanian-Yugoslav
border area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital of Central Province to Ban Use of Leaded Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Changsha, the capital of central
China's Hunan Province, is to ban the sale and use of leaded gas
starting July 1, according to a circular issued by the municipal
government recently.
</P>
<P>
Violators will be penalized in accordance with relevant rules
and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Changsha now has 120,000 motor vehicles which produce 438 tons
of harmful pollutants each day, posing a threat to the health of
local people, especially to children. The city's number of
vehicles is expected to grow at an average rate of 10,000 units a
year.
</P>
<P>
The city has began spreading the use of unleaded gas since 1998
and the use of unleaded gas in over 100 gas stations have reached
70 percent.
</P>
<P>
China now has approximately 13 million motor vehicles, and the
number is expected to exceed 20 million by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Urban air quality reports regularly released by the National
Environmental Protection Agency show that auto emissions have
become a main source of air pollution in some major cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali King Approves New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Nepali King Birendra Monday
approved the 16-member new cabinet formed under the premiership of
Krishna Prasad Bhattarai, Radio Nepal said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet comprises the prime minister and 15 ministers.
Bhattarai holds concurrently the posts of defense, home affairs,
foreign affairs, royal palace and women and social welfare, the
state-run radio said.
</P>
<P>
Mahesh Acharya takes over the Finance Ministry. Former home
minister Govind Raj Joshi is transferred to the Water Resources
Ministry while Chakra Prasad Bastola is the minister for
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Yog Prasad Upadhya is not a member of either
houses of the parliament. Under the provision, he should win the
membership in either house within six months.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is scheduled to take oath before King Birendra
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai was appointed the prime minister last Thursday after
his Nepali Congress won a majority of 110 seats in the elections
to the 205-member House of Representatives held on May 3 and May
17.
</P>
<P>
This is the first majority government in Nepal in four and a
half years.
</P>
<P>
Six governments had ruled the kingdom in the past four and a
half years after the mid-term polls in November 1994 produced a
hung parliament, where no single party commanded a majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
