<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Hits Northwest China's Qinghai Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 5.6 on the
Richter scale jolted Zadoi County of Yushu Tibetan Autonomous
Prefecture in northwest China's Qinghai Province at 4:10 am (
Beijing time) on May 30.
</P>
<P>
According to China Seismological Bureau, the epicenter of the
quake is located at 32.6 degrees north latitude and 93.4 degrees
east longitude.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary reports said residents of Zadoi County in southern
part of Qinghai Province and Baqen County in northern part of
Tibet felt the quake slightly.
</P>
<P>
As the quake-hit area is sparsely populated, the property
damage and casualties there have not been available so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Island Becomes China's Biggest High-Quality Banana Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China's southern island province
Hainan has an annual output of nearly one million tons of bananas,
making it the country's largest banana producer.
</P>
<P>
This year, the province increased the acreage of banana
plantation by 100,000 mu (about 6666 hectare) to 400,000 mu and it
is expecting to get about one million tons of high-quality of
bananas.
</P>
<P>
The island province's tropical climate makes it an ideal place
for bananas and at Dongfang, Ledong, and Sanya they grow all year
round.
</P>
<P>
The province began to grow bananas on a large scale in 1991 and
the increasing returns have attracted more investors. Last October,
one Hong Kong businessman signed an agreement with the city of
Dongfang to spend a billion yuan (about 120 million U.S. dollars)
on a banana plantation in the city. The project is expected to
produce 250,000 tons of high-quality bananas when it is completed
in 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxes Paid By Overseas-Funded Companies in China Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing, the capital of China's
Jiangsu Province, collected 727 million yuan in taxes from local
overseas-funded businesses during the January-April period of this
year, a 38 percent rise on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
The increase is a result of local efforts to improve the
investment environment, which helps local overseas-funded
enterprises do business better, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months, the city added 101 overseas-
funded enterprises, bringing the number to some 3,210. The number
of companies each paying more than 5 million yuan in taxes
annually is now 11.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish-backed Nanjing Ecrisson Communication Company, for
instance, had 2.56 billion yuan in sales during the four-month
period and paid 153 million yuan in taxes, nearly 10 times the
figure of the same 1998 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
