<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy to Expand 5 Pct Next Year: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
forecast over the weekend that the country's GNP will expand by
"more than five percent" next year, sustaining its strong recovery
seen in the first three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Post quoted the bank's governor Gabriel Singson
as saying that higher-than-expected growth of gross national
product (GNP) of two percent by March will fuel more robust growth
in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
The figures for the first quarter of this year released by the
National Economic and Development Authority (NEDA) increase the
likelihood of GNP growth of over five percent next year, Singson
said.
</P>
<P>
"This is very encouraging and very good for the economy,"
Singson said.
</P>
<P>
NEDA's report showed that the country's GNP for the first
quarter of 1999 expanded by 2 percent while gross domestic product
(GDP) grew by 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the government may seek higher growth targets from
the International Monetary Fund, if the uptrend continues in the
next quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
