<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT May 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said on Sunday
NATO bombing was weakening Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
resolve but would only stop if he met alliance demands in full.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made after Yugoslavia's Tanjug news agency
reported on Friday that Belgrade accepted the "general principles"
set out by the Group of Eight as a basis for bringing peace to
Serbia's Kosovo province. (UK-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union (EU) foreign ministers will
exchange views on Monday about whether their current concept of
enlargement strategy is still valid and for how long.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges will set the stage for a more formal review at
the European Council in Cologne, Germany, later in the week.
European Report, a EU publication, said that what the 15 ministers
will look at is the continuing absence of an overall plan for EU
relations with the countries on its Eastern borders. (EU-
Enlargement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- European Union (EU) foreign ministers are going to
choose an option to solve the dispute with the United States over
EU's banana regime during their discussions about the preparation
of three bilateral summits at their monthly General Affairs
Council in Brussels on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The three summits are the EU-Canada on June 17, EU-Japan on
June 20 and EU-US on June 21. The EU-US summit will be accorded
the lion's share of the ministers' time, EU sources said. (EU-
Banana-Regime)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Foreign ministers of the 15-nation European Union (
EU) are to meet here on Monday to discuss Balkan issue during
their monthly General Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
The 15 ministers will debate the measures in regard to a
Stabilization and Association process for the countries of south-
eastern Europe. (EU-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Sunday
sent a strong-worded message to Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud
Barak, urging him to break his silence and stop the intensified
Jewish settlement activities in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Barak is called upon to lift his silence and take steps to
stop measures taken by Netanyahu which will destroy the peace
process," said Tayeb Abdul Rahim, Secretary of PNA Chairman Yasser
Arafat, referring to outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the National Conference to Confront Settlements held
in Ramallah, Abdul Rahim also called for physical confrontation
against Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza. (Israel-
Palestinians-Settlements)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Aryeh Deri, leader of Israel's powerful religious
Shas party, submitted his appeal to the Supreme Court on Sunday in
a bid to overturn his conviction by the Jerusalem District Court
on charges of graft.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said that Deri presented a 75-page appeal to
Supreme Court President Aharon Barak on Sunday morning. (Israel-
Shas)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African President Nelson Mandela is still
hopeful that two Australian aid workers jailed by a Yugoslav
military court would ultimately be released, the president's
office said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Mandela was asked by former Australian
Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser to intercede on the Australians'
behalf.
</P>
<P>
Mandela then phoned Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin in an attempt to secure their
release. (SAfrica-Mandela-Australians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Slovakia's presidential candidate Rudolf Schuster was
declared winner in the country's presidential election Sunday,
ending a 15-month period of the country without a head of state.
</P>
<P>
The Central Election Commission announced that in the second
round of balloting held on Saturday, Schuster won 57.18 percent of
the vote, against won 57.18 percent of the vote garnered by rival
candidate, former prime minister Vladimir Meciar.
</P>
<P>
The voter turnout was 75.45 percent, according to the
commission. (Slovakia-Presidential Election) 
</P>
