<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sofia Worried at NATO Raids on Yugoslav Towns Near Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria is concerned over NATO's
overnight airstrikes on two Yugoslav towns near Bulgaria's western
border, a spokesman for the Bulgarian Foreign Ministry said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, NATO fired missiles on several parts of
Pirot, a town about 60 kilometers from the Bulgarian capital city
of Sofia, destroying apartment buildings, a factory and a TV
transmitter. NATO war planes also bombed the TV transmitter in
Dimitrovgrad, outside Pirot, on the border with Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
"We have expressed to NATO once again our concerns over the
interests of the ethnic Bulgarians living in Yugoslavia," said the
spokesman, Radko Vlaikov, urging NATO to avoid risking hitting
civilian and non-military facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
