<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vurbanov Elected President of Bulgarian Volleyball Federation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sofia, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Agriculture Minister Ventsislav
Vurbanov was elected President of the Bulgarian Volleyball
Federation at a general meeting that lasted nearly five hours
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the delegates voted for him.
</P>
<P>
"I will not work alone. I will build a team of professionals
to rely on. I will make the work of the federation transparent
and will insist for the introduction of normal transfer rules,"
said Vurbanov, adding that he would do his best to help Bulgaria
get back to the World League matches.
</P>
<P>
Former present Valentin Zayakov, who has been holding this
position since 1992, left the general meeting not long after its
beginning protesting the election of chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
The general meeting was convoked six months after a serious
rift emerged in Bulgarian volleyball, creating two separate
federations: one of Zayakov and the other one of Dimiter Zlatanov,
who was elected President of the Federation in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Over the conflicts between the officials of the two Federations,
the International Volleyball Federation barred Bulgaria from
international tournaments and championships untill May 31, the
deadline for holding a general meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We can say now that Bulgaria is again in the family of world
volleyball," said Ralf Andersen, President of the European
Volleyball Federation and Vice President of the International
Voleyball Federation. Andersen had been sent to the general
meeting by the International Federation to monitor the procedure
for the election of a new federation president.
</P>
<P>
The International Volleyball Federation is expected to cancel
Bulgaria's punishment on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombing Stops Only If Yugoslavia Meets NATO's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said on Sunday NATO bombing was weakening Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's resolve but would only stop if he met
alliance demands in full.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made after Yugoslavia's Tanjug news agency
reported on Friday that Belgrade accepted the "general principles"
set out by the Group of Eight as a basis for bringing peace to
Serbia's Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
"The mere fact (Milosevic) is making such an offer does
demonstrate that the pressure is telling on him. We must make sure
we keep up the pressure until we get a settlement that meets our
full objectives," Cook told reporters Sunday afternoon after
meeting Kosovo Liberation Army leader Hashim Thaqi in London.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he denied the reports that Britain was planning to
send an extra 50,000 troops to the Balkans as part of a Kosovo
invasion force.
</P>
<P>
"Any decision of the kind that there has been speculation about
would be a decision for the full alliance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reports on British newspapers on Sunday claimed that NATO had
secretly planned a 150,000-strong ground invasion of Kosovo, for
which Britain would contribute 50,000 troops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
