<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provisional Results of S. African Poll Expected by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The provisional results of the
South African general election would probably be announced by June
3, the next day after the votes were cast, chief electoral officer
Mandala Mchunu said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) would then deal with
any disputes, for the final results to be announced within seven
days after election day.
</P>
<P>
"We should be able to issue a provisional result by June 3,"
Mchunu said in a television interview in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The IEC' high-tech information system would enable political
parties to verify election results as they became available.
</P>
<P>
About 600 computer working stations had been set up at the
IEC's election result center at the Pretoria show grounds.
</P>
<P>
"Quite a number of these have been assigned to political
parties so that they can verify the results as they come in," said
the electoral officer.
</P>
<P>
Incoming results would be counted by computer.
</P>
<P>
Vote counting would take place in full view of political party
agents and observers. Vehicles transporting ballot boxes to
counting points would all be escorted by security staff.
</P>
<P>
Mchunu said 445 satellite dishes deployed throughout the
country would be used to transmit results by computer, including
from remote areas.
</P>
<P>
Presiding electoral officers would first convey results to the
election center by telephone and fax machines.
</P>
<P>
The figures transmitted by computer would serve as a
verification of those already received.
</P>
<P>
Mchunu said the 600 computers at the Pretoria election center
cost about six million rand (about one million U.S. dollars).
Sponsorships from the private sector, including three million rand
from United States computer tycoon Bill Gates, helped to cover the
expense.
</P>
<P>
The computers would be sold by tender to public institutions
and other buyers after June 2.
</P>
<P>
Mchunu expressed confidence that sufficient measures had been
taken to ensure a peaceful election. Security staff from a
contingent of about 90, 000 police and soldiers would be deployed
at voting stations as from Monday.
</P>
<P>
They would especially maintain a strong presence in high-risk
areas.
</P>
<P>
"I have not received any earth-shattering news about points
where voting will not be possible," Mchunu said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted a high turnout of voters.
</P>
<P>
"By 10 a.m. (0800 GMT) on election day people will start
realizing that voting is not a painful process, and the numbers
will start rising."
</P>
<P>
Voting stations will be operational from 7 a.m. (0500 GMT)) to
9 p.m. (1900 GMT) on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
