<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers to Review Enlargement Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) foreign
ministers will exchange views on Monday about whether their
current concept of enlargement strategy is still valid and for how
long.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges will set the stage for a more formal review at
the European Council in Cologne, Germany, later in the week.
European Report, a EU publication, said that what the 15 ministers
will look at is the continuing absence of an overall plan for EU
relations with the countries on its Eastern borders.
</P>
<P>
Until the Kosovo crisis jolted EU complacency, the general
belief among the EU member states was that the enlargement to ten
countries of Central and Eastern Europe was a respectable, and for
the time being, largely sufficient strategy.
</P>
<P>
During an one year period from March 1998, the pre-accession
process was running as smoothly as could have been hoped, and the
front-runner candidates were making the sort of progress that had
been expected, the EU report said.
</P>
<P>
A comfortable sense of gradual evolution was settling over the
EU with accession dates for the leading applicants settling in a
reassuringly medium-term perspective from some time beyond 2003,
stretching perhaps another ten years into the distance for the
slowest of the ten, the European Report said.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, believed that
the emergence of the Kosovo conflict exposed the inadequacies of
the approach to South-East Europe, and also revealed weaknesses in
the EU's general planning.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive pointed out that the void between the EU and
Russia was made very evident by the split over the merits of the
NATO's airstrike against Yugoslavia. And the need to offer
immediate support to countries like Macedonia and Albania as they
bore the brunt of the refugee crisis ran the risk of leaving
formal EU candidates in the region feeling neglected, it added.
</P>
<P>
A commission spokesman said here Friday that "the situation in
South-East Europe provides reasons for moving as fast as possible
towards the enlargement in Central and Eastern Europe".
</P>
<P>
The Berlin summit two months ago went a long way to resolving
the financial difficulties, so the EU should now concentrate on
this. "It should not give a signal that South-East Europe is
depriving the candidates in Central and Eastern Europe of
attention," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
