<DOCNO> XIE19990531.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers To Decide Options On Banana Regime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 30 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) foreign
ministers are going to choose an option to solve the dispute with
the United States over EU's banana regime during their discussions
about the preparation of three bilateral summits at their monthly
General Affairs Council in Brussels on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The three summits are the EU-Canada on June 17, EU-Japan on
June 20 and EU-US on June 21. The EU-US summit will be accorded
the lion's share of the ministers' time, EU sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon Brittan, European Commissioner for External Trade, is
expected to present a report on the EU's efforts to comply with
the banana regime following the recent ruling against the EU by
the World Trade Organization. Sir Leon will also highlight a
number of points concerning the EU ban on hormone-free and
hormone-treated beef from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, EU's executive body, unveiled three
options on May 26 for reforming its controversial banana regime
and ending a bitter trade dispute with the United States on the
issue. The options include an end to the quotas on banana imports,
retaining the quotas but removing the limits of bananas from
African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) nations, and setting a new
quota which would be shared by ACP and Latin American exporters.
</P>
<P>
The options are designed to meet the demands of the world Trade
Organization which condemned the regime in April.
</P>
<P>
The commission also hopes one of the options will be agreed
swiftly to limit the damage from 186 million worth of U.S.
sanctions on the EU, which were also agreed by the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
